\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid16392069 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Suzie Annette - Hills it was then. Freeman now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And your address here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 249 Ladbroke Grove. W.10.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And you're a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Yes, I am a widow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember what year it was you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember what year it was you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 The twelfth of November - 19 - 1891.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 373, Portobello Road, the corner of the next turning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Five years. And then we moved into - Ladbroke Grove. And - I lived there for many years, and
 then I went down to - Westcliffe to live with my aunt and uncle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where at Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 3 Finchley Road, Westcliffe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is that in Sussex?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Westcliffe on Sea, Essex. And - then I - I came back here - and - we lived at - 390 - I think it wa
s - Portobello Road, but it was at a junction, and the front of the house - was at - was in Portobello Road and the back of the house was here, it was right up on the corner there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you lived in Labroke Grove for many years, about how many years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I've lived twenty - twenty - wait a minute, twenty years - I lived in - at 249 Ladbroke Grove, and I've been here thirty-four years, and I lived in Chesterton Road - five years, that's the second turning from here. That's - the only places that I
've lived in except at Westcliffe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But you say when you moved from Portobello Road to go to Ladbroke Grove when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many years did you stay in Ladbroke Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh we stayed in Ladbroke Grove 'til I grew up, I mean - well, I don't know how many years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 About ten or fifteen years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, must be. Fifteen to sixteen years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How old were you when you went to Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I went down there first - when I was taken ill - after I had been ill, and 
then - I - I - came back - I went to school down there a little while and then I came back here, and - I went to work in - in the Post Office, but I was only there a few months - when I got scarlet fever, rheumatism, etcetera, etcetera, and - I went back 
to Westcliffe - no, after that I went to do some writing for about twelve months to a lady in Ladbroke - Ladbroke Grove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of writing was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh I used to write letters for her. Answers to questions and - make a - answer to appo
intments, to make appointments, and - and then I went down to Westcliffe - she recommended to me - a German who was a - come over from - where they make all these - tobacco merchant he was, and he was a - a German and he had children in - in - Germany and
 
he bought these other children over to Westcliffe, and I went to live with them to show them - I was with them about - eighteen months, I went to live with them, as the family, and show them all round Westcliffe and - teach them little bits o English that
 
they didn't understand sort of thing - and - then I got married from there. I was married at Westcliffe. And - and I lived at Westcliffe until my baby was born - in 19 - 12. She was born the eleventh of September, 1912. Well, when she was - nine - months 
o
ld I had - to come up to London, and I was in hospital - for four months, owing to the - through something happening through the birth. Well my mother-in-law looked after her. And my husband was working, and then the war broke out. And - my husband went t
o
 - join the Royal Fusiliers. And then he - his father - claimed him into the - Army Service Corps, and they were sent out to France and they were out there all through the war. Well - I - stayed with a lady - in - Oxford Gardens, and - her name was Miss B
e
ulah Tripp, she was an opera singer, and - I lived with her for a little while, and then my furniture was bought up here, and - I lived in - I had my furniture bought up here and I lived there, well she died. And then I moved to Chesterton Road. Well of c
ourse the war was on. And the first - Christmas of the war, I - I did the Post Office - service just for two or three days, you know how they did. How it was arranged, and then - I -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What were you doing with the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No, in the P
ost Office - delivering letters, it was to do - delivery, anyway - after that - no, where did I go after that, when we moved into Chesterton Road - I went with my friend into whose house I'd moved - and - we went on munitions at Park Royal, I was a checke
r. Of components. Well - I - my little girl was very ill and I gave it up - and then I went to Clement Talbot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s it was then. And - in Barby Road, and I did work there on those statistics - a department and all sorts of things we did there. And - then - I wa
s recalled - I made an application to - go on the - I can't think of the name - Ministry of Pensions at - we had a house there - there - Gloucester - Gate, Gloucester Terrace, Kensington, and then I worked there right until my husband came home from the w
a
r. And - of course then when he came home, his friend opened a shop in Portobello Road, confectionary and toys etc. etc. And this man, he wasn't married, so my husband made me leave that job to go and manage his shop. And I was there 'til - oh I was there
 
about three or four years and then - the shop - collapsed, well it didn't actually collapse, but the lease ran out and he wouldn't renew it. And then I moved to 297 Ladbroke Grove and I lived there twenty years. And - my son was born in 1922. Well I did n
o
 work from - 1922 'til he was eighteen months old. And then I worked twenty years at the hospital, as a hospital orderly. And - I worked in the laboratory and I got - I was ill, and the doctor said that I wouldn't work in the laboratory any more, and - I 
s
aid, well then I would leave the hospital, they wanted me to take up - work in the sewing room and all that sort of thing, but I said, no, I didn't want it, so I - went up to Country Hall, and - he told - told me that hereafter I would only be only to do 
clerical work. Well then - I had an appointment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  at the Associated British Cine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
mas, Golden Square, and I was accepted and I worked there for fifteen years 'til 1958, when I collapsed in the street, just round the corner there and I've done no work since.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever do any part time jobs while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? No. Oh no. Only what my mother taught us to do, we all had to take it in turns, one day somebody swept the stairs down, the next day someone bought the coal up, the next day some
one went shopping with mum. And - we all had to - make our beds, shook our beds in the morning, and go to school, Mornington Road Board School. And - no, I didn't - I didn't have any - any other job after that. Only at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Going right back, you say you lived in Portobello Road and then you moved to Ladbroke Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And then you moved back to Portobello Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Can you remember why the family made these moves, why did your father and mother change houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well - we -
 we only had - somebody come to live - with us, to look after us children because - my father had a bad operation, and he didn't do much more work after that. And then my mother went out and she used to take on - on - cooking - but she used to supervise -
 
continental cooking and do soirees and dinner parties for all sorts of people you see, and - this old lady and gentleman, he was a retired - sailor, and - she was very elderly, well they used to look after us you see when mum - perhaps mum would be away t
wo or three days if she had a big dinner party for perhaps two hundred people or something like that. But we were never left alone. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? I had - well my mother had, in all, twelve children,
 there were six boys born by her first husband. And - her first husband and two children died and one child was born dead and that left me with two brothers And my mother married my - her first husband's cousin. And our name was changed from Wheeler to Hi
lls, and then my mum had five girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So by the time you were born there were just two boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 There was only my two big brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How much older were they than you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 They were ten years older than me. And - then my mother had me. And eig
hteen months after my sister was born. And - I think it was two or three years after that - my mother had another little girl. And she died when she was eight months old, she was born without a spleen. And then - my sister - May was born and my sister Kit
 and that's the only one I've got left now, my sister Kit, down - who has just lost her - daughter-in-law and son-in-law.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How much age difference was there between you and the youngest daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Me and - me and my - youngest - sister? Oh - ten years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So they were quite evenly spaced out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. There was ten years be - between us. And - yes, that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say your father had an operation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well, if he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How old were you then, were you still at school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I was still at school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What was the operation for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
And - he - he - he had an operation on a - on his groin, and they cut a - a sinew and his leg was - one leg was shorter than the other, you see, well then he - he did a little bit of jobbing gar
dening but he couldn't do much because he - become an invalid you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That was his job was it, gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
That was the - that was the job when he died you see, but - he hardly ever did any work, that's why mum had to go out you see, but we were
 brought up strictly - under - there was never any drink or cards or anything in our home. I know somebody bought me a game one Christmas, snakes and ladders, and - oh no, it was my birthday, I beg your pardon, it was my birthday and this lady sent me a -
 snakes and ladders, you know, that we used to play with, and - we had this children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s party as they were then, not like they have now you can bet, and - I know I - we had a red rent book - and I wet it put some - and painted my face red, and I went down - 
stairs and saw my dad. And he looked at me as if I'd got fever, he said, there's something wrong with her, he said, we'll send for the doctor at once, he said, something dreadful's happened to her. Well I'm terrified out of my life. So I said, it'll all w
ash off, it'll all wash off.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Ten. Because my youngest sister was a baby in the - a cradle. And - anyway I've never, all my life, I've never used make up, I've never used a lipstick in my life, or anything, we never were al
lowed to and I never did. But we were bought up and this lady bought this snakes and ladders and my father made me tear it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That's how strict we were. But believe me - I think I was about the naughtiest in - that ever went to th
at Sunday school. But - nothing - nothing wicked, never steal or anything of that but just - devilment you see, I'd got these brothers older than me, and they made a god of me. And of course they're both - died now, since the 1914 war. One died and buried
 in Eton churchyard, and his son is buried there and my other brother is buried at Wimbledon. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you close to your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 I beg your par}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 don?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you very close to your brothers before they died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, my dear, yes, I - id
olized them and so they did me. I know - I know once I did something, I don't know what it was now, something very trivial, and my mother said, if you do that again, she said, I shall slap you. My youngest brother said, no you won't. He said, you hit me, 
d
on't you hit her. But I was a little devil. And - of course I know one day the men came round, we used to call them the clickers because the men used to play those bones - spoons, you know, and I was out there dancing and my father came along - he said, i
n
doors. Of course all the kids used to dance to the organs in the street and have a - then another time I had a - rope thrown over the lamp post - I was swinging round the lamp post this way and this way, and - then we used to sit in the - on the kerb and 
p
lay marbles and - back and fore stones and - hopscotch, we always made our own pleasure, then - twice a year - at school, for a penny you could buy a ticket to go to the magic lantern, and - it was the time of the boat race, and they used to give us - a l
i
ttle - blue bow or - Oxford bow or Cambridge bow, whichever you belonged to as you came out from this. You had to buy the ticket at school, and at Christmas you got - perhaps an orange and an apple or something - or something like that. And - that was our
 pleasure. Then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you make anything of birthdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would you make very much of birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, my dear, we always had children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s parties. And - oh yes, I was a born actress my dear, I had to be the head one
. And I never forget once - oh I was about - I wish I had that photograph to show you now, I was seventeen, and - I wrote this - little play, and we played it up at - a church in Harrow Road, Chu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ch Hall in Harrow Road, and my sister was in it and that bli
nd girl, she was in it, and - I had a - that was a - I had trouser suit on you know, oh my dear I thought I was lovely. And I was the Prince, 'cos I had to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you wrote it yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. Yes, I always wanted to be a writer. But of course I was never educated up to that pitch. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where did you start off at school, was it round here the school you went to to begin with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Five years old I went to Mornington Road Board School, that's just up the top of that road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How do you spell that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Wornington. Wornington Road Board School. And I was there 'til I was about fourteen and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Then you say you went to Southend Technical School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, I - I - because I - I wasn't the age to leave school you see then. I pa
ssed the ex seventh and - and - according to - winning the scholarship I should have stayed on and perhaps worked my way up to - something different but I didn't do it. You see? But of course I had this -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did you specialize in at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh
 - I wanted to take up - I wanted to be a writer, I - I mean I - those days it was different to what it is now, I - I always wanted to - to do something that - something that - on my own, on my own initiative if you know what I mean. I know I sat up all n
i
ght to write - write that play, it was called two Kings. My sister was a - was a Prince and I was the King or - vice versa, I don't remember now. And we did it one evening, and there were all about - what - I suppose fifteen or sixteen could have been I s
u
ppose. I can't remember our ages now, not looking back on it. But we always had - had - we used to get - I - on a Saturday - a Friday evening I used to go round to a Jewish lady that lived in Bassett Road, and - I used to light her gas, because - they wer
e
 - strict orthodox Jews, and the Friday - evening until Saturday evening - sunset, they mustn't touch light you see, so I used to go and - light the gas - for her, and I used to get sixpence. Well out of that sixpence - I used to buy a tuppency - screw of
 tobacco for my dad - and I used to give my two sisters a penny each and I had a penny each, and a tuppency bunch of - a penny bunch of - daffodils or whatever you got for your - for your mum. That's how that sixpence was spent. Well then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Why don't Jews have light between the hours you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Well it's something in their - in their religion, I don't know what it is, I don't understand, and - I know I used to go round there, they were lovely people, and - I know - what - what I used to love about 
it was, she - I always had - this - fried fish. Piece of their fried fish, oh was nothing like that. Oh I used to think that was marvel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ous. I didn't even want to take the sixpence. Of course sixpence those days was a lot. And I know this - aunt of ours, w
ell she wasn't really our aunt, she was a lady's maid to Lady Brassey, in Berkeley Square, and she used to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  come and see my mum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
 'cos mum used to arrange dinner parties there, and she came over to see us. Well, if she came on a Sunday I had to go to church w
ith her. And I used to count fourteen hundred with the sermon - while he was preaching, I hated it. And - but we used to go to Sunday school, we were quite happy there, and I took my little sister on one occasion, she was in the baby class, so I said to h
e
r - we always used to have a - a penny to put in - in the plate. So - the teacher said to her, when she had to put her penny in the plate, she said, whatever you give to the Lord, you will always get something in exchange. Well after Sunday school was ove
r
 my - kid sister's still waiting in the seat - in the - the pew. So I said, come along. She says, I'm waiting for me ha'penny change. So - they put that in the magazine, they thought it was very funny. But - as a child - I must have change. Now if - if I 
h
ad a penny I would spend a ha'penny. But I must have change. Now that - that - that's stuck to me all my life you know. But there's so many things that - I look - back on now, that have changed - very very much today. People have changed. And - attitudes 
o
f people. But there's not the - kindness and the - severity in people as there was those days. I mean my mother and father they were very very kind but they were also very severe. And - and - we daren't - not even by a look - show any animosity against th
em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you sort of resent that at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh no. No. No. I - I wished I could have brought my children up the same, but - my daughter, in all her life she never answered me back. I never had a rude answer from her, she was lovely - and everyb
ody loved her around here. They - they always called her Phyl, Phyllis her name was, everybody, and the day that - of her funeral, I shall never forget. The whole crowd out of there, bunches of flowers - from - all the trades people. I never never expecte
d it and they collected about - ten pounds to give to her little boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Going back to your mother and father did your mother work when you were born, just after you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no, she didn't - she didn't go to work then. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Haw old would you be when your father had the operation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I think all this happened about when I was - a - about ten or eleven. When this old couple came to - live with us, their name was Cheetham. And of course we had extra room in the house then, why we move
d we - we had the offer of a flat with more rooms you see, and also the landlady of the house where we lived - her son got married and she wanted our flat, but I mean there was no animosity against that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So which flat were you in at this time, was this the one in Ladbroke Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Had a top flat in Ladbroke Grove up there, and I had - we had the upper half of this house here, my - daughter and her husband and two little girls, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But just before your father had the operation, where were you living at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh we had three rooms in - in Portobello Road. I think -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you moved from Portobello to Ladbroke Grove then - back to Portobello, then you went to Westcliffe on Sea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When the two people moved in with you, which house was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
in Port - in Portobello Road. Yes. I think the number was 390. Portobello Road. And - oh it was different to what it is now my dear but - all here - the - people along here, they - they had their carriages, and i
t was a treat for us on a - Saturday morning to have a penny ride up to - Westbourne Grove and see all these people going in the shopping in all their crinolines and - black high legged boots. And - I know my - two sisters had - new ones. And my mother ha
d my old - my Sunday ones, mended for me for school. And I carried them to school for a week in my hand, I wouldn't wear them. Because the other two had new ones and I didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 By and large did your mother make the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Make ou
r - make our clothes, my mother made - made everything for us. Yes. And - we - we all had very very long hair and sometimes - oh it - how - however late she came home at night she used to wash our hair, and - and see that we had everything clean for schoo
l.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 This is when she was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes, work - this old Mrs Cheetham her name was, Auntie kate we used to call her, she was dear old soul. And of course the old boy, he - he used to tell us all stories about over the sea and - and - 'course some were true and some were not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was this the couple who lived with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes, this was - and then you see - old Mr Cheetham died, he was about seventy odd, and a little while later - no, Mrs Cheetham died first, she had pneumonia, and - he died a few weeks later in - he just didn't want to live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But it was your house they lived in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes, oh yes, they lived in - they - they lived. They had a room in our house you see. And - they - oh - no, they didn't work, they didn't have any pension, not - it's only what mum earned that kept the lot of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you meet them initially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? They came to see the - the people next door, and - the people - who let - had lived next door had moved away. They came up from Chatham, and t
hey said they had nowhere to go so - mum took them in. And the old, lady had - at that time used to work at Bradley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s but - she - had to give up the work for some reason I know - and I know my mum was very very worried. Because of - of - things were very hard for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Apart from the Cheethams did you ever have any other lodgers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 The Cheethams weren't really lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
enever - never had any lodgers, and - we always had - children in to - tea parties, mum used to make cake an
d - ice it and - and - we used to play games and so forth and so forth, but - nothing like today, I mean you didn't have - elaborate presents, I know Christmas we used to get - an orange and an apple, and - a bon-bon, and a - a toy from Woolworths, sixpen
ny toy from - sixpence ha'penny toy rather from Marks and Spencer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s or whatever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would you have anything special to eat on Christmas day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well - on Monday - we always had - on Sunday we always had - either - a piece of beer - or - a leg of
 - lamb or mutton it may have been. Tuesday - that was - a cold dinner and beetroot and a baked potato in it's jacket, and bread pudding. And we come home tonight - at night, and in the - in the winter - in the fender - in front of the open grate, there w
a
s a big dish of - dripping toast. And - every night at nine o'clock we had to go to bed, after saying our prayers, and my dad would bring in to us a cup of - condensed milk made with - Nestles milk, we had that in bed and he'd tuck us up, and that would b
e the end of our day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When would you have the main meal, would that be at night time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we came home from - school to - dinner, and - then we had - Tuesday - Tuesday mum - or - Auntie Kate used to get or mum used to get - used to buy - oh - meat was then only four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 pence a pound, sixpence a pound, she used to buy - big - beef, carrots, onions, potatoes - I mean you could get a dinner for a family for a shilling. And - potatoes were fou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 r pound for tuppence. And - or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 anges - four a penny. And - what
 we had - we had much better food than what we get now, much more nourishment in it and no tinned stuff. Only tinned milk, mum used to get for us, Nestles milk, and - then on a Tuesday - on - on Tuesday we'd have this - stew, and - Wednesday perhaps we'd 
have - shepherds pie. It was - it was a routine. And - we never - always at Christmas we had a big big joint of roast beef. And we - never had chicken or anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have many relatives come round on Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. No. Mum - my moth
er's - relations we never saw. Nor my father's. He had twin sisters and they lived at Luton. And we never - my dad was born in Luton and my mum was born in Shropshire, Bridgnorth, and - we - we never saw any real relations. There - old Auntie Kate was the
 
old lady that looked after us, and - no, she wasn't our real aunt - that was old Mrs Cheetham, we all call-d her Auntie Kate and Uncle Jack, and then the - oh we idolized her, she was dear old soul, and then we used to have - this lady used to come and se
e
 us occasionally, and - I know she came one Christmas time and she gave me a two shilling piece a florin, so - I said to my two sisters, I'm the eldest, you can have sixpence each and I'm having a shilling You see? So - I went round to the - shop, and I g
o
t a shilling and two sixpences, I had the shilling and I give my two sisters sixpence each. So my mother said to me, what have you done with that money? I said, I've given them their share and I've got mine. My mother took my shilling - she gave the kids 
a
 each - a penny each to go out and buy sweets, so I got nothing. So she took my shilling away - so as my sister went out to buy her sweets, I waited for her to come in, I snatched them out of her hand and I went in the lavatory and ate them. And what I di
d
n't eat I put down the sink. And when I came out my mother said, for that you get nothing. She didn't hit me. She said, you get nothing, she said. When somebody gives you something between you, she said, you must share it equally. And she said, you do tha
t
 all your life. And, she said, a slice off your loaf, and a cup of tea out of your pot you will never miss, and she said, always give. And do you know, that stuck into my mind 'til now. We never heard a bad word in our house, no cards or gambling or drink
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is that both your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. My mother wouldn't have brandy not when she was dying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you find your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh yes. Yes. She was - very well educated. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did she do before she was married? What kind of work did she do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
She - she lived with - both her parents died - and - she lived with a relative, and there was some money left for her but she never had it because when her parents died and she went to school down - do
wn there - these people were supposed to be very religious, but - I think she was only about seventeen, as far as the tale goes - and - she was married in the morning - to this man who - knew that she had this money, and his - father - his uncle was - a m
i
nister. Well they were married in Wales - and - she was with this - these people who were looking after her - and - they were married - she was - they were married in the morning, and in the afternoon - this husband - and the - uncle - were drowned in Bal
a
 Lake. She was married and a - and a widow in twenty - less than twenty-four hours. That was a - that was when - that was her first marriage, and then of course she came to London, and - I don't know what became there, my father was a gardener at St James
's Palace, and li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 ved at - lived in there in a bof}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
fey they lived as under-gardener, and - my mum - I suppose, as far as I remember, she was in - in domestic service. As far -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it your mother that had the two boys or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That was my -mm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your two elder brothers, were they your mother's sons or or your father's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, yes, they - you see, she was married - I mean that was nothing, that was - that was just one day. But - she never got any of the money or anything, she came up
 - up here to London. Of course all - most of the kids that grew up with me, I mean when they left school they went in gentleman's service, you had two of everything and a pair of black stockings and - or two pairs of black stockings and a little wicker b
asket and off you went in gentleman's service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you had two elder brothers who your mother had by her first marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But you say her husband died on the same day that they were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. When she was - sixteen or sevent
een - she was - married to this man, and he was drowned the same day. And instead of my mother having that money, I don't know what it was through or anything about it, this is only what we my mum told us - as we grew older, she came to London, and she ma
rried - and - she - had these boys -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So she was married three times in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. And - she was married, and she had these boys, and she lost her husband - in Farraday Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That's round here is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Next turning. 53 Farraday Road, she 
had these - opposite the Fire Station, she had - there was Willie and Walter - Charles - a dead baby, Jack and Sam. That was the boys. That was my - her first husband.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say there were only two when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. Well - her first - her h
usband died - she had a dead baby, and her two little boys died, one was three and one was five. And the school board man came round, and those little children - that big house you see at the corner, the little window that's in the side that's a foot clin
i
c now, the men used to make the coffins in there and my two little brothers, of course I wasn't born, used to go and talk to these men. Well both those boys died - with black measles. And the school board man came round - and their father had only been de
a
d a few weeks - and the school board man came round - and he said - you haven't sent the children to school, and so my mother said, no, go and look where they are, there was two little coffins in the front room. So - that was that. And then I don't know h
ow long after that that she married my dad. And of course I was the first girl, I'm the seventh child of a seventh child. My mother had -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That's supposed to be lucky is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I had six brothers - she had six brothers older than her. But my two brothers - one - one worked for Buchanan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s the - whisky people. He - he was a - driver, and my other brother, he joined the army - when he was fifteen. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did they live in the same house as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your brothers, or did they leave home after a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh no, no, they - they - my next brother was ten years older than me, and the next one was - was - fourteen years older than me, the eldest brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But did they still stay in that home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, yes, of course they did. 'Cos their - their - their - my father was their - cousin you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many rooms did you have in these houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Which house is that now, all of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 The - the - top of the road here, in - went - right through the Portobello Road 
there was - two rooms in the front and two at the back. And the - the front - the - two rooms looked out into Portobello Road and the two - other rooms looked out into Portobello Road, right up on the junction here, at the end of the road, where it joins 
Wornington Road.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That wasn't the house you were born in though was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, I was born - in the corner of the next turning, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many rooms were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And we had all the upstairs there, four rooms upstairs there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So you had four rooms in both places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was the second one bigger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Probably you moved for that reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, we had four rooms all the time. And of course when - when - my - when - when - we had this old couple come to live wi
th us, they - had a put you up, we had a put you up, my sister and I - in - in the - in the front room, and - and - of course then my brothers and left home, one - one was in the - army and my other brother - he - he went to - oh I think he got married as
 far as I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How old were you when the Cheethams moved in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? We - every - everything happened as - as near as I can remember about - ten or eleven. Everything seemed to happen that year, as far as I can remember as regards ages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You know you said you got the scholarship and went from Wronington school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you mean you went to Southend in Essex Technical School?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. I went there because - I - I'd had a bad - I'd had pneumonia, and my aunt and uncle had a boa
rding house - at Westcliffe, and I went to stay with them you see but - I had - I went - had to go to school down there but it was only for a few weeks because - when I was better I came back home, I wouldn't stay with them. But - when I went to - to - to
 Mrs Collier - it was through them that I was introduced to - these German people, they bought a house, Clemhilly on the Lees, down at - Westcliffe and of course I went and stayed with them until I was married from there you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So it was a different place in Westcliffe the second time, you went to a different place in Westcliffe the second time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
We were brought up strictly - I mean children today - they're - they turn their people out when - if - if they want a party. But no. Our mum and dad - was to us - they were our god.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say they were quite strict with you, but in a very sort of kind way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes. Oh yes, we - I know - I - I know that - we would - never allowed to use bad language or - I know one day I came home and I
 - I said to my mum - do you know what? So she said, no, I don't know what. So I said, well the lady in Ladbroke Grove that lives next to the church, that's an old girl used to live down there, she used to sweep the church out, we led her a dog's life, an
d
 - I said she said bugger. I ended up with a clip, she said, don't let - don't you dare let me hear you say that word in this house again. Now my dear it's a figure of speech. Never bad - never a bad - we were poor - but we were happy. We never knew - any
thing - as I - as I told you, since that man nearly strangled me down here -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it a very rough area round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No. No, no, no, not - although it's quiet now, we never have any trouble here, but the other end of Ladbroke Grove and throu
gh Portobello Road there's terrors there, but not here. Round St Stevens Square and Condal Square, a dreadful place. We never hear - we never hear anything here. As it is now you know - the only thing we have here is the traffic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you were a little girl I'm thinking of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it very bad then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we - we used to think it was funny, there used to be a man go about here, he was about six foot six, and we used to call him Long Nell, his name was Neil. Well as we were kids he alw
ays used to give us a ha'penny in the dinner time, he was a labourer, and - he didn't have any wife. Well when we saw him coming up the road to go in the Eagle public house, of course us kids, we all used to talk to him. Sometimes he - he'd buy a big bag 
o
f sweets and give us, another time - we - I know once he gave me a new ha'penny, I thought that was wonderful. He said, it's a brand new one, only just been made, and I took it in and showed it to my mother. And - he used to give us a ha'penny each, well 
he used to go in the pub, used to get a half a pint of beer, a penny. And he used to go in the pub and it was beer then, well by the time he came out - he was drunk, and there was always a fight. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 This was at lunchtime was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, oh this
 is in - yes, sometimes in - in the afternoon this was, of course the pubs were open all day then. 'Til twelve o'clock at night, oh yes. So of course us kids - I only lived opposite the - right opposite the Eagle we lived. And - in fact my elder daughter 
w
as very friendly with the people who had the Eagle then, the Olafs, and - anyway - we used to watch old - Long Nell - he - he would always fight. And - somebody would argue with him and they used to do it for annoyance really. Well he was always too drunk
 
to hit anybody. But he - he was miles high we used to think, and these long dirty old trousers, and he used to fight like this. And - then we'd see the police - two policemen come up, and then they couldn't get him up to the police station 'cos he was fig
hting so they used to get the trolley. It was a long - like an invalid carriage with a shade up. And they used to strap him on that and us kids used to follow him to Harold Road police station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did the employers think about him being drunk all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh my dear, he was - he was only on a Saturday. Yes, he was a labourer, everybody loved him. I mean the - even the police, they - they only took him when he - broke a window up there and when he got spiteful, but - otherwise - you'd see - he u
sed to be fined ten shillings. Five shillings or ten shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That's quite a lot though isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes. Those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was there much rowdiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Rowdism here, no. No, I can honestly say no. Not this end of Portobello Road, Labroke Grove or Portobello Road. I'm sure -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You've always lived up this end have you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes. Yes, I've never lived - past the station. No, the shop - the - I managed - down Ladbroke Grove was just opposite the entrance to Portobello Road school, just - a f
ew shops from Tavistock Road. No, I was very very sorry when - I had to give up my job there because I could have been there for many years, I was doing - the - dead soldiers - effects, you know, all their - paying out and all that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 This is after the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. That was the first world war of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That was during the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes. Yes, I was there - all - all that time. But I loved it - I loved it on - when we were on munitions, especially night times. I was on t
he Ambulance Brigade and we had a terrible raid there one night. And there was six of us doing the first aid. Well we had this bomb fell and it - demolished a house in Harrow Road, and - 'course it wasn't as bad as this war - last war was, and - I know we
 
stayed on the bus to see the damage - be - as we came off night - duty, and this particular night - when I looked round for the people we had a train in there that used to - we used to load up with the - components, I used to have to count them and weigh 
t
hem at the end of the bench you see and book them, and - of course the girls, all along the bench, about twenty girls, ten each side, used to do all the polishing and assembling and I used to be at the end count and weigh them you see, there was so many i
n
 each box. And then I - of course I used to have to keep a sheet you see and - write it all out. And - then - at a meal time - someone - had an old piano there and they - we used to sing all the old songs for an hour you know and then get back to work. We
l
l one night we were there and there was a - we thought it was a terrible raid, it was indeed, and - when I called out for a - called out for the - to go round to the benches - I couldn't find the other five. So the train was in ready to - go the length of
 
the dock, so the better - and I could feel these lights overhead so I dived underneath the engine, and I stayed there 'til it was over, I didn't have any casualties. Oh no, I was very - as a child. I was very very happy. And I knew my husband when I was f
ive years old, and I've had a very happy married life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you meet him, you say he was at Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He lived opposite to me in Westcliffe - he lived opposite to me in Ladbroke Grove, five years old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And then he went to Westcliffe and you went to Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He came to Westcliffe to live with my aunt and - and uncle, he got a job down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I thought you meant you met him at Westcliffe?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no. No, he came down to Westcliffe, we got married down there because my mother
 said I should never marry him, because he was a Roman Catholic and I wasn't. And we were, we were married at registry office and I sent him home with the marriage lines, I never came. And - then we were received in the church. But - I loved him -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have to become a Roman Catholic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No. Neither of us did, we didn't change, but - my children were Roman Catholics and until they were old enough to change. And their children are Roman Catholics so - my - that granddaughter's Roman Catholic and h
er two little boys, but Margaret, she's gone back to Church of England. You see - you - when children - earn their own living they must do as they like. But as my father always said, as long as you - are under my care you will do as I bid. Not as I ask bu
t as I did. And that's what we had to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who do you think gave most of the guidance in your house, your mother or your father or both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well, it was both because I know one day I wanted to go somewhere - and I asked my mother. No - she said, you 
can't. All right. I'll ask daddy. I went into my daddy, he was reading L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
oyds newspaper, I can remember it so plain. So I said - daddy can I go so and so? He looked up, and he said - what did mummy say? I said, mummy said no. Well then no it is, and he wen
t on reading. Never - never any unhappiness in our house at all, and - my daughter and her husband were married and they lived happily, but no one - ever went up into their home - they - all the children had all their parties in my room - he's an extrover
t, he is now, he's taken that little boy away to Hemel Hempstead, they do all their own washing, cleaning, cooking, no woman goes in their house only his two daughters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about when you were a girl, did you have anyone come in to do any washing for 
you or did you do all the washing yourselves, did your mother do the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No - my mum used to do the washing in a big tub. A great big tub and a - and a wringer on the end. She used to do all that washing and ironing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did she ever take in washing for other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no. She had enough of us. No, we always - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever help your mother because you were the oldest girl, did you ever help - around the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We all had our jobs, on - on a Saturday - I used to go round 
with mummy shopping one Saturday. And - my sister had to sweep the stairs down. And - clean the stair rods. My brothers had to - get the coal up. Clean the windows. When my dad couldn't do. And - the - little one, she used to have to hearth stone the step
s. We used to get - tuppence each for that, and that's what we spent Saturday night, after we'd had our bath, and our hair washed - Saturday afternoon we used to go down Portobello Road and spend that tuppence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That was your pocket money, was that just for the day or did you get pocket money for the rest of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we - a - perhaps we'd get a ha'penny or a penny, well they couldn't afford it. But my mother used to buy - she used to get a pound of mixed sweets, four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 pence a pound, apple drops
 and pear drops, we used to get - some in a bag after our dinner every day, just a few. That's all we had. And I know someone gave me a penny to post - some letters for her, an old lady, and - and - and I had - I got her a bottle of stout, and when I told
 
my mother - I got it from the off licence you see, so I said Mrs Birch - a poor old soul, she died in the work house - she used to come to us on a Sunday after - about once a fortnight, to have a cup of tea and - and - then she used to go back on the bus 
to work house in Kensington. And - she was another old neig}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
bour. And - now something else I was going to say all of a sudden. That's what goes from me when I'm trying to say anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you'd got two older brothers, did they help you younger ones in any way? Apart from their tasks for your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, you see they - they both went - they both went into the army, my younger brother went into the - into the - army Service Crops, and my older - elder brother - of - of course he - that's his - before 1900.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But before they went away did they help you in any way, you were about ten when they went away weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, they used to - come home - from their jobs, I don't know what - I can't remember what jobs they did, and - come home an
d - wash and go out to the pictures or - or something. Sometimes they'd give us three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 pence each to go to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 penny hop down Portobello Road. Then we had to ask could we go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But you'd be older then wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And - yes, and - but after that - and of course I - I was about twelve and - my sisters younger. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 As the oldest sister did you help the younger girls in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Help what dear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your younger sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, no, we used to go - Sunday school, Monday - we
 used to go to the Band of Hope. Wednesday - we used to go - to - the - Guild of Holy Innocents, over there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is that a Catholic one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And - it was a high church, it's - it's higher church now than it was, and - Fridays - we used to go - we had a 
shopping - Thursdays - we could go - to the club, and that was an old - old shop that had been painted out, belonged to St Michaels, and - was a sewing class, and Fridays was games. So that was all - we had, but we didn't want anything else. We - we didn'
t - we didn't - have anything, and then - in the winter, my dad used to come and meet us. And we only had to come across the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 This would be after school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes. Yes, a little - six to seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You'd have these roast joints and things like that in the middle of the day would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, yes, we - we went home to dinner, because our school was only sort of that road. It was only as far from here - not so far as from here to the station. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would all the family be there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 All of - we always went home to dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your father as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes, all of us. No, daddy didn't used to come home to dinner, not when he was at work, but - when - when he - after he was - he gave up his work, of course he was home altogether
, well then of course the old gentleman and the old lady had died by then. And - dad used to look after us, I can see him now peeling the potatoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He did help around the house did he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We - we - only had to do our jobs that we were told to do, we had to strip our beds, in the morning -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your father did odd things around the house as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever wash the clothes or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no. No, mum did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about things like washing up, would he ever do that, or cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No - sometimes I'd help - I - daddy used to wash up and I used to wipe up. And then my next sister used to put the things away. The little one didn't do anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your father ever do any cleaning around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your father? How about decorating or repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, he didn't do anything of that. Only - only pot plants that we had on the window still. We had all sorts of that, and - clean the parrot out, I hated the beast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He used to do that did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever sort of help to dress you or undress you and bath you or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, mum used to buy our clothes - do you mean buy our clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he help get your clothes on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. No, I mean -
 no, because - well of course he was working then, mum used to see to us, and when she didn't see to us of course - we used to help each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever give you baths or anything on Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. No. We had a big bath tub. That was - we had
 to wash down every night at the sink and - and - strip down to our waists and wash every night at the sink and at nine o'clock we went to bed and dad used to bring us - when we were in bed he used to bring this - this cup of milk made with Nestles milk. 
I
 can always see that. Always - we always had tinned Nestles milk, but - always on weekends - we used to get - we used to get a pint of - pint of skimmed milk for a penny, that used to make Yorkshire puddings and that sort of thing. But - cows milk we - us
e
d to call it, 'course it's all cows milk more or less, and - but - always - we'd always - mum'd always make a - about twice a week, a - a bread pudding, and - we'd have that hot for our tea, when we came home, or else she'd make a - a pastry with the bits
 
of - currants or something in it. We always had something. We never - we never came home to - piece of bread and butter, and we never had margarine in our house. We used to get a pound - a pound of best fresh butter, shilling. I can always remember that. 
A
nd I know once when we were very very hard up - my mum cut her hand on a soda water bottle, and she couldn't work, and - she was home for some time, she had it all stitched up, and I know we were - very much on the rocks and the boys used to bring their m
o
ney home - and - I know that - we - we didn't go short but - we knew there was something wrong. And then I said to her, to my mum one day, I said, will you - will you let me go out - out cleaning doorsteps? My mother said, no I will not allow you to go cl
eaning doorsteps. But I said you get a lot of money. So she said, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember ever having anything to do with the Parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we never had anything - never had anything from the Parish, only - once - Doctor Ensal came in and saw my fathe
r - after he'd come home from Kensington Infirmary it was then where he'd had the operation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your father ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, and - and not only that he used to tell - tell us - history stories. He was a great reader. But - while I was 
at the shop, in Portobello Road, my daughter was - seven or - now let me see, no she wasn't, she was nine, my daughter was nine - I was at the shop, and my - brother was sent home wounded. And - my father was looking after - my dad used to come down to th
e
 shop, and - my mother was away looking after my brother when he came home, I told you he had germs of TB injected into his back, in Daresalaam when he was a prisoner, and he died and he - and he's buried in Eton College grounds. He was maintenance engine
e
r there. And his wife used to do all the lovely laundry for the wives, you know, the teachers - the - teachers' wives. And of course they had their lovely house there, beautiful place. There were six houses there called Willow brook, between Slough and - 
a
nd Eton. Well - I was in the shop one day and - my dad came down, so he said - he used to come down - to have dinner with us or tea with us you see, and - of course my husband was home from the war then, and that's - when he played me up - he - he didn't 
go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
to work for a long time when he came home. Because his father, I told you, he dropped dead in Ladbroke Grove, and he came home from the war and it was a long time before he took up work again. Of course I was - managing at the shop. It seems a long time 
but it could have only been a few months or a year perhaps - looking back on it I - I can't remember the exact time, well my dad came in on this - day to have his dinner. So he said, Mr Tennison's come over, that was an old colleague of his, and he said h
e
's come over from Ireland, he said, so - I won't stay. So he said - I'm going back home, he said, and I'm going to look after - Willie, that was my sister's boy, he was ten, and he said - Harry and May, that was my - brother-in-law and my sister, they're 
g
oing out somewhere on some business, so he said, I'm going to babysit, I'm going to look after him So she said - he said - she's left her some sandwiches - for me and Mr Tennison and we'll stay - and look after Willie. Well - my brother and - brother-in-l
a
w and my sister went out somewhere, and my dad went home. Mum was away down at Eton, Windsor - and - or rather Eton, and - the lady that lived - in the basement, she came up with a telegram, and - Mr Tennison had just left, and my dad was sitting reading 
t
he paper, looking after the little boy, and - the telegram came from my sister-in-law to say that my brother had died. That was on the fifth of March. Well - my father opened the telegram and he dropped down unconscious. The lady downstairs - called the p
olice, and he was taken into Kensington Inf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
rmary - he'd broken a blood vessels - the ar - aorta blood vessel, and he'd - he was dead. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What year was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 192 - 3. 1923. That was - yes, that was 1923, my - brother died, he was thirty-six.
 On the fifth - of March, and my father - died two days later. Well my mother was away - and - well - when - I went down to my brother's funeral, and - I said to my sister-in-law, I said, will you tell mum that dad's dead. We didn't tell mum at the time, 
because she was so upset.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where was your mother at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
So - pardon? She was looking after my brother which - and he only called out for his mother, he didn't want his wife or anybody - when he was dying. 'Cos he died in - in their house do
wn there. 'Cos they brought him home from a hospital at Reading, and - the - mum was looking after him, well anyway, he - dad died two days later, well the next morning my sister-in-law bought my mum up, it was only a shilling fare then workman's train up
 
to Paddington, and my husband went and met them, and brought my mum round to the shop. Exactly twelve months to the day that my father died my mother was buried. Five days later after my mother was buried, my elder brother died, 'cos he was shot - all his
 - his back was all shot away, down at - at - Wimbledon. And - my mother was dead - exactly six weeks when my little nephew, ten years old, came home - and - a boy had hit him in the ear with a pencil box. And - it caused an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 abscess}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  - a ti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
us media, an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 abscess}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  in the middle ear. They operated on him - in Ken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
ington Infirmary and he died. Exactly six weeks after my mother, so we had five deaths - in - in a year. In thirteen months. And we've just had the same again. Two brother-in-laws, Hilda's husband, and -
 Leslie's wife, and - Ken's cousin, twenty-three. That's - that's all happened - since - November.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Going back a bit can you remember how old your father wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 
uld be when you were born rough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I - I can't remember, I must have been -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He was sixty-three when he died you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, and I - I - my daughter was born - I must have been - I must have been - thirty. 'Cos he never saw my son.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So he'd be about thirty-six when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was he older than your mother or younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
The same age as my mother. With - within a few months. Mum's birthday was the eighth of April, my dad's was the fourteenth of February. My dad was about two months older than mum, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Apart from when she went out to arrange this cooking she didn't do any other work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes. No, she didn't do any other work, that was all she did, I mean, she was - a trained cook, and - and she used to arrange all these things and - and - she used to go out doing these - soirees they called 
them or something, she used to go for two or three days at a time preparing you see, and she used to supervise it all, she was a marvellous cook. She - and I know this time that I'm trying to tell you that we were so hard up she went to work - she went to
 work at - from a Royal Society, Burlington House for some people named Harrison. And she went there on three occasions, to - cook for them, at different parties they had, and - she used to walk home from Pi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 cc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 adilly to save her fare, come home - walk home a
t midnight so that us kids'd have something to eat. She used to walk home from there so our kid - us kids had something to eat. We never owed anybody anything, and what we didn't have we went without. But we were never hungry, we were always kept clean.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who would look after you while your mother was away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Dad, yes. Yes. Yes, that was sad the way my dad passed out like that, he - he just - passed right out, of course the boys they called him dad, they didn't - make any difference, they loved him.
 I never saw him in a temper. And I never heard - heard a bad word out of his mouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say that he was quite strict with you but he would never hit you or anything like that when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What hit one of us? Yes, he hit me with a new
spaper once, and I cried and cried and cried 'til the people next door come in and asked what was the matter. The woman said, yes, and if I was your mother I'd give you another one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your mother ever hit you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. She threatened us lots of times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How would she threaten you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
She said that - if I - you - are you telling me the truth? Yes. Are you sure? Yes. All right. If I thought you told me a lie, she said, you'd never forget it. But - that was all it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So it was all words?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What she said went my dear, one look.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of person do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Well - my mother hoped - that - I would do anything except go into domestic service. And - that's all I did, cleri
cal work. My two - my - two sisters, they work - worked as shop assistants. One - one used to serve in the grocers. And one in a sweet and toy shop. And - my brother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  used to work for Buchanan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14888113\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s, I don't know what he used to do there, I can't remember, and then my - other young brother, he - he was about sixteen and something, he - he went in the - he joined the army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of things do you think your mother and father expected you to hold up to in life, what kind of standards to live by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Wel
l they always thought that we would try to live like them which we did. Because - my daughter - they - they - they just idolized her, and - and my - my mother and my son, and - well we just bought them up - the same as we were you see, I never drank, I ne
v
er used a cosmetic, and no drink was ever brought into my home. My husband used to drink occasionally, but - never any drink brought in our home. And my son-in-law, he never looked at a drink. He smokes. My son smokes and he drinks, but I mean - not to ex
c
ess. But - as regards - drink and smoking, gambling or that, I'm not interested. Somebody said to me the other day, you're so fortunate with the different things that you do, she said, even at your age, she said, why don't you do the football? So I said, 
no, I - I haven't got any - inclination to do the football.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you had these houses in Portobello Road and Labroke Grove when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What was the sleeping arrangement in them, you say you had four rooms, were they all bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No - we three - three little girls - the three girls had a bedroom. At one time, and the two boys had a put-u-up - in the front room, and mum and dad's bedroom, and - but - of course - my brothers had left home when the old people come to 
live with us, so they had their room, you see. So - and then us - us - girls had a - had a put-u-up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What do you mean by a put-u-up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Beds that you put up, folding beds, mum - mum used to put them down at night and fold them up in the daytime, th
ey looked like two tables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would those rooms be used for other things then as well as bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Of course they were bigger rooms than this, I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But were they used as bedrooms during the daytime or were they used as living rooms during the daytime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we had one big living room, and then you see the boys had their put-u-ups - in there at first. Well then after that - my sister and I had the - had the - put-u-up, 'cos after - after that you see I went down to Westcliff and then my 
two little sisters - had the put-u-up, and - the boys had left home, and - well then there was only those two there then. Well after that when I came back there was only - mum and dad and - me and my two sisters in the - in the four rooms you see. So we -
 oh we had heaps of room to play.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about kitchen and bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We never had a bathroom. We had a big bungalow bath. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What's a bungalow bath look like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 A big iron bath. And - we only had those here. They used to have - we used
 my kitchen - as a - as a bathroom, I had a boiler in there, and there was a toilet next to it. And - this big bungalow bath, that used to be under my bed in the other room, upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about when you were a little girl, was the bath in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we used to have a bath - bath in - the kitchen and our hair washed, there was a big sink and - mum used to get this bath, used to hang up outside on a - on a - big zinc bath and - we had a - a - a boiler, a gas boiler, and that - we used to hea
t the water on that, we never had hot and cold water, I never had hot and cold water upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You used to have a bath every Saturday?
