\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16008431\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 boil. When I went 
to get them my dear there was none there. Well I'm - I don't know where the - I - I don't know what happened, I thought to myself, well I couldn't have thrown them away. So - anyway I looked and there they were wriggling all round the landing. Of course -
 
they were full of life you see. So I - I had - my husband came in at the time, so I said, look at them things crawling round there, I said, so he - he got - picked them up and chopped 'em up and put them in sink, turned the tap on, put them in the water a
n
d they were cooked. And after my ma-in-law had eaten them we told her what happened. And of course she knew they were all clean. Oh it caused quite a sensation. Yes, we used to get winkles - tuppence a pint winkles, and - sometimes - we'd have - for our t
ea on the Sunday we'd have - a - celery and radishes, and bread and butter, and - well we always had something but it was all good wholesome food.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You never had any tinned meat or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 any tinned stuff? No, only Nestles milk, that
's all we had, and we used to have - I used to get skimmed milk on the Sunday - and - always got a pint of fresh milk when old - when old auntie came, 'cos she liked cows milk we used to say. I couldn't bear it. But this - big lump - of - Nestles milk put
 
in the - put in your - in your - hot water, my dad used to bring that in for us, with usually a - biscuit or piece of bread and butter, when were' in bed that was when we were small. 'Course as we got older we used to have - do our homework or - we had ho
me lessons to do there right from we were quite small, not til you got in the ex-seventh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You wouldn't have anything like poaching going on around here would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16008431\charrsid5646288 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 y what dear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Poaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh they used - I'll tell you what they used to d
o here, poach your clothes off the line. Yes, that's - if you left a line out all night they - you'd lose them, and - the boys used to catch pigeons. Mm. They used to catch the pigeons round here. Yes. I know - one boy - Gustav we used to call him I think
 he was half Italian, I don't know which half but still - he - he'd say - I'll bring - I'll bring some, his father had the ice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16008431\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
cream shop, and - he came one day with two pigeons, and he brought them up to my mother so he said, two for a shilling. So my mother said, no you've stolen them, you - I don't want them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did he do with them, eat them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I don't know what he did with them. We didn't - we never had them. No, I only - I know I was quite a big girl - there's - when - one of - I was quite a 
big girl when my oldest brother came home from the Boer War, quite - I felt a big girl, and then that was the first - time I can ever remember we had a turkey. And we cried all the time we'd eaten it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well, it used to run about like the chickens next door. And I - next - next door they had chickens. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So there were sort of poultry things kept in this part of London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh they had a - the old lady, old Mrs Green, I think she had chickens downstairs, next door had chicken
s, all the way along there had chickens. Of course we all had back yards and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But you didn't have any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And - all we had was the parrot, and it - that was a he, that never laid anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you go anywhere like parks for mushrooms or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh we used to have - oh yes, we - have had mushrooms, fried mushrooms and that but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You wouldn't go out and pick them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, never here. Only when - when I was down at Westcliffe we - we used to go out in the early morning ther
e, these - German children and I we used to think it was lovely, but they were very very wealthy. Oh it's a beautiful house they had, right on Southend front on - Clovelly the house was, on the Lees. I think there was about sixteen rooms in that house. Ye
s
, they had a German servant but - I took these girls out - I was - I was married - I - I was living with these people when I was - when I was married, and - this - Hannah, that was one of the daughters, she spoke very good English, so - we all went down t
o
 Southend, and - walked all along the front and - up Southend High Street and came home - on the tram you see, and then we just walked down - Valparty Road into their house. So - the - as we were going in the house they - they had a maid and she opened th
e door, and she said, where have you been? So this girl started singing all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16008431\charrsid5646288 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
e nice girls love a sailor, and they thought it was ever so clever you know. Oh well they were lovely people. They really were. Thought the world of my husband, he - he used to - 
come round and - yes, he left his - job up here. He was working for his - grandfather. He was an upholsterer and loose - made loose covers and - art - all art decorating - curtains for altars and all that sort of thing he used to make. That's where my hus
b
and first - started, you see, but then of course he - he went to work for different big firms after that, and then - he - he met Mr - Kennedy North, and he introduced him to - Sir Edwin Lutchens, well then - that's when they went down and painted the roya
l procession, my husband did the bordering and Kennedy North did the - artistic work on it. Yes, and I - we went down and stayed - my husband then was staying with my sister-in-law, see, at Willowbrook, my brother was working there then. Yes, it's -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember anything like your mother having less food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you ever remember anything like your mother having less food at mealtimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Less what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well only the time 
I'm telling you about - that - when my dad - was in hospital, and she couldn't go to work 'cos she cut her thumb, and I can remember - we - we all had our dinner - and - no, we'd had our dinner and we were having our tea, and we had bread and dripping. I 
n
ever forget that, and - my mum had - I can see my mother having that now, a slice of bread, and she poured some boiling water on it and put some salt and pepper on it, and I never forgot that, and I said, do you remember mum when you had bread and milk an
d
 you never had any milk on it. She - and that - that stuck in my mind. But there was only - oh it only happened a - a - and I know when - when my brothers came home - my - younger brother came home on leave he gave my mother a sovereign. And - oh I though
t - I thought - we were all going mad when we had this sovereign. And then - I had to go over the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16008431\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
road to get some shopping, and the people's name were Shears, and I had a ten shilling - a - a half sovereign and as I was going down the steps - 'cos we had a
ll the floors, they were - old Mr Rogers shop, he was the old boot maker, and he only had the shop and the parlour you see, well we had the - all the four rooms upstairs, four or five rooms, four rooms and a kitchen, in Telford Road, and - he was - as I w
a
s going out this slipped between my fingers. Well I thought I would have gone mad. So - I went back and I told my mother, oh well, she said, it's very sad, she said. Do you know I got up four o'clock in the morning and I raked all in that gutter and I fou
n
d it. I prayed all the night. I never went to sleep, I pray - I said my prayers and I said to my May, my sister - I - I said, will you ask God, I said, that I find that money. I said, because I said - what will mummy do? I said, that's the rent. So - she 
- she said I'll ask God. So we both prayed for it and all through the night I kept saying please God help me to find that money, and I did. And do you know I've had the greatest faith in prayer since then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you allowed to talk during meals do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well - you - yes, to say please or thank you or pass you something. We was always too hungry my dear, we was always - ready to eat.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was your father there at breakfast times or was it just you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He used to have his breakfast before we - before us. Because he used to leave home - half past six or seven in the morning - those days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was he still at St James's Palace in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And - no, he wasn't at St James's Park then, that was before they were married he was at St James Park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where was he after he was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
He was working for a firm, I can't remember the name. Oh McKellars their name were, and he used to do jobbing gardening then you know, go round gardening but - but before that he used to - go out 
and arrange - from the time he left - St James Palace he - and he was married to my mum he used to - go out and arrange these - gardens in peoples houses and do gardening like that. As far as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about your brothers, because they'd probably be out working by the time you were old enough to sort of remember having breakfast?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, I - yes, I'm very - they were at work but when my - younger brother was - well they were both in the army -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 They weren't even there anyway the time we're talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Can you remember whether you could ever ask for second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Well - I - if we wanted it we had it, but - I mean there was always plates of bread and butter - or what have you on the table but - we were never ke
pt short if you wanted more you could have it, we didn't have two pieces put on our plate and that was that. But - only on that one occasion when my dad was ill and mum had cut her hand, she opened a bottle of soda water and it split her hand right open. 
Oh I can remember that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? My mother used to say - sometimes - your eyes are bigger than your stomach. But - at your age you must leave a clean plate. Because otherwise you will never grow up. But - yes, we were all fine children I mean nothing to be ashamed of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was there anything that you didn't like which you were made to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, my dear. Nothing, only - broad beans. I couldn't bear - I couldn't bear those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have to eat them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No. Mum didn't used to put them on our plate. But peas and potatoes and - everything - I know when - the time I'm talking about, we went home one day, and - my mum - fried a big lot of potatoes for our dinner. And -
 we didn't have anything else. And I know that - on the Saturday - we had eggs for our dinner. And my little sister said to me, she said, what - what's the matter with mum, she said, we're having our breakfast for our dinner? She - that's all we had, and 
bread and dripping for tea, but we were never hungry and we never wanted for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have what you were given?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What was put on our plate we had, we never asked any 
questions because if our nose went up my mother used to say, there's little children abroad - and they - they're starving, they're living on a handful of rice. And I used to say to myself, fancy chewing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What would happen if you wanted something like the salt, could you just help yourself or would you have to wait for it to be passed?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
For what dear? No, I used to say to my little sister, pass the salt, or - we used to reach out for it, it was in the middle of the table. There was the cruet and - with the - bottles in it. I can see that now. Vinegar and sauce and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we - none - none of us were left handed thank God, we - we always - used our - knife and fork, we alwa
ys had to put a - we were never allowed to have - hold our fork like that. You - you had to use it that way. And we were never allowed to use silly words - next door to us there was a little a girl, and she used to say to her mother, I want a eggy for my 
d
inner, and I want this - something silly, and my mother used to say, eggs. And - not gee-gee, horse. You - we were taught - we were taught to - speak properly, plainly, I - I don't know about - educational big words but - we knew what we were talking abou
t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No. Oh no. That was the only thing I can remember my sister having a rubber doll - on her high chair, a little tiny rubber doll, oh no. You had - you had to say your grace and you had to eat your f
ood and wash your hands afterwards, and go to school and you take your -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who would say grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. And you used to take - take your dirty knife and fork and plate - and put it out in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who said grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, mum used to say it. Or sometimes we used to say it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
When we'd all finished you know and put our chairs back and - and - we'd take all the cups and saucers and plates out and put them in the sink and - mum'd take the cloth off and p
ut the coloured cloth on. That's how we were brought up, I don't know about anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 The same table was used for playing on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, we had a big - big square table - oh great big table like this. That used to be scrubbed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever have many visitors come round for meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Many visitors? No, only school children. No, we never had any - my father never had any - we never had any of my mum's or my dad's friends in. And that's funnily enough with my - son-in-law, he never wanted any
body in - in his house, and if anyone came to see my Phyllis they come down in my room He - and he's the same now. People used to say round the corner, when he used to go shopping - they didn't even know he was Phyl's husband, until the - she died and the
n of course when he used to take the little boy out he always had his arm round his - and that - always had his arm round his shoulders, oh we had a dreadful - time when he died - when she died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? Yes. Mm hm. To - to - well, Sunday - Saturday and Sunday - we always had - had - we - we always had our meals together. Of course dad used to - come home - after we'd had our tea. And - we - we'd go down, we had a little tiny ante-room, little sli
p
 room - well we used to play in there, oh it was a tiny little place, well - we had a board up, my brothers put a board up for us and that's where we used to - we used to - have - acting, we used to do all sorts of acting and playing down there. And the k
ids next door used to love to come in there. But - that's all we ever had, my - the only people that came to see us was - was - this lady I was telling you about and - no, nobody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you all have the same places, would you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we used to - mum and dad used to sit at the - each end, and - my two sisters used to sit there and I used to sit next to dad. That was always my place. And when this boy from next door used to come in to tea, if Ernie would - used to come i
n sometimes on the Saturday - he always sat next to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How was the meal served, would your mother serve it up?
