ion without we had somebody with us. We were all played - up here, we - never allowed to play in the street, only - outside the house - perhaps - she let us play hopscotch and then she'd come with a broom and wash all the chalk off. And - of course as I -
 
when I was about twelve of course we used to - play hopscotch and swing round the lamp post and - go round watch the people dancing to the organ, but as - as small children - wouldn't let us out of her sight. I mean that's how it was. If - if we went to K
e
nsington Gardens - Mrs - Mrs Cheetham had used to come with us or else - mum - we'd go with somebody grown up and then mum would bring the tea along. A girl who lived next door, she had a cousin staying with her - she was an orphan but their name was Stag
,
 Cissy Stag was one - girl we couldn't get on with and this girl was grown up, I - I thought she was a - ever so old but I think she was about sixteen those days. Well we used to get on the bus - up to Westland Grove, of course the fifty-two buses weren't
 
running then, we used to get on the bus, a penny on the bus up to - Arthur's Stores it used to be, that's where the Odeon's built now, and then we'd walk up through the turnings to - Kensington Gardens, and then we had to stay in one place 'til our mother
