\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 party in the garden when it was one of my sister's birthday, oh we thought it was lovely, we had - two coloured umbrellas - li
ke, stuck them up there, we - oh we were miles away in our estimation. No I'm very much afraid that - as children - we didn't - go very far away from home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But you didn't mind that did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We didn't want - we didn't want to, it - it never came 
into our minds. And I know once when - I tell you I followed the Salvation Army down nearly to Shepherds Bush. That was - my mother nearly went mad. When my dad came to pick us up - pick me up rather, I was in there having - hot cross buns I called it, wa
s buns and - milk and - sweets. I said, I'll - I'll come again one day. They said you won't. Of course - they said, or they'll keep you here altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What denomination were your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What religious denomination were your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Church of England. That church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did they go every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No. My father used to go but - my mother used to go occasionally, she used to take us - she used to take us sometimes in - on a Wednesday evening, and - then
 it was the see missionaries that had come from abroad. I know we - we had a coloured man there, well you never saw a coloured man those days, Father George, I can remember that and - he came from - from America, he knew my father strangely enough, and - 
h
e came and - as we came out he stood at the church - door as we came out from the church and - somebody behind me said, if you touch that - if you touch his coat you'll be lucky all your life. So I remember as I come out I touched his coat like that and h
e
 looked round at me, and - he said, have you - have you enjoyed it? We said, yes, it was - lovely, and then again - in the mission hall here - on a Wednesday evening, if they didn't have a - have a meeting at the church, we used to go round to the mission
 hall, 'course it's all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
nocked down now, just up on the - like the third turning from here, Rackham Street it used to be - and they used to have sale of work there and - games and - some days, and - actually - it belonged to our - it was the church hall fr
o - from St Michaels but it was called St Martins Mission. We used to go there, and - games and needlework and - everything - there was something there about every other night. But Tuesdays and Thursday I think we was home but - Fridays was games and - Mo
ndays I think was needlework, I've forgotten now how it was, but that's how it was, that's the way we spent our time. And in the wintertime my - in the winter and the dark nights my father used to come and meet us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you remembered a Band of Hope as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we didn't go to a Band of Hope, we didn't have a Band of Hope, ours was the mission, it was called St Martins Mission, the Guild of Holy Innocents, I think nobody could have been worse than us kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was your mother ever a member of anything like the Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s Institute or Mothers Union or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Do I remember what? No. She never believe - never believed in that, or Mothers Meetings, she never had time. She never had time for - any of these meetings. The only thing - the only
 place my mother ever - used to go to - and I don't know where that was but it was a sort of place like the school of Good Housekeeping. She - she used to go there sometimes where they taught cooking. And - and I know she used to go there for a refresher 
course but where it was I couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 She was doing a lot of work really so she didn't have all that much time to go about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No. I know when she was home - home - when she - when she wasn't working we'd come home from school and - s
he'd been washing and ironing and - washing every day and - ironing and - we had clean white pinafore every day, to go back to school. And - also - she taught us darning, and - knitting - One thing I could never do, I could never crochet. But knitting yes
. And needlework - patching, we all had to do that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you a member of the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh - we used to sing - sing - on a Wednesday evening over there in a choir. But - they only had choirboys Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So you weren't a member of the church choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We only went - we only sang in the church choir at the - at the Guild.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So you didn't go on any choir outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did the church have any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Have a temperance club? No, not that I can - not that I can r
emember. Singing the pledge as they called it? No, if they did, I - we didn't know anything about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. We always had to say our grace - whether - my mother was there or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who would say grace then, all of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
You - just used - and we always had to say our prayers, and - as I tell - said, my father used to sing. He'd got a lovely voice, he used to sing and - and with this boy Ernie, he was in the boys choir over there, they used to sing - harmonize an
d oh we used to think that was lovely. But apart from that we - I never forget when we had this phonograph, well - we nearly took it to bed with us, we thought it was wonderful to hear - hear a voice and nobody talking you know, and see - see nobody.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 It would be still quite new in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, it was a little cylinders like that, you put it on like a roll and wind it up and there's a little trumpet, and at - then I know my father bought one - a second hand, he bought it - off a f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 riend of his, with a big trumpe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 t, His Master's Voice. Oh that was wonderful. All the kids in the street come to hear that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have any friends popping in and out of the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did we have many friends? Only school friends. Only - friends that lived n
ear. We used to go in their house sometimes and they used to come in ours, but - it was just that - well we never - we never wanted anything - there was - my dad was always home in the evenings, I can never remember my father going out at night, never. Ne
v
er my - when he came home from work - he used to bring the Evening News - and - he'd wash his hands and put his slippers on and his paper under his arm and he'd come and have his tea, and then - he'd read the paper and we'd do our homework or - whatever w
e were doing, painting or sketching or - whatever it was in the - and unless he took us out, down as far as Workwood Scrubs for a walk. But I can never on any occasion - all our lives remember my dad going out on his own. Never.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would he ever go out with your mother, just the two of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Sometimes they used to go out, but - but very very seldom, it was only to - to see somebody - who he worked with or - somebody that was ill or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I suppose after he had his operation he'd be at home all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh after - after his - after he'd had this operation he was - he walked very lame, we - he didn't - go out at all, I can remember he used to see somebody who wrote books, and - this man used to come to our house and - named Delamere, M
r Delamere, and he used to come to our house and we all got a penny each when he came, if we'd be quiet while my dad was talking to him. And he was writing a book on flowers, and - we thought after - we used to call him the flower man. Dad, here's your fl
ower man come. Yes, we used to get a penny each those days when he came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He came to ask your father about flowers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, all about gardening and - this man used to draw plans, I know, I can remember that. I know used to have big sheets of paper
 like this and he used to draw, and I used to think, I wish I could draw like that. Used to sit down and do this, a path, and so forth, there was the bed and - then he'd do this and sketch it all on the table, we'd sit and watch him, we used to think it w
as wonderful. But apart from that - we used to - be downstairs in our little sitting room, our ante-room as we called it, we got some kids in there - we were acting, playing - Cinderella and all that sort of - things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters, you say you got on very well with your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get on with your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 With my sisters? Oh we - we never quarre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 led - the little one was the - trouble. I know when - oh, how old was I - I must have 
been twelve and - Joey Freeman, that was my husband - was, he lived at number three hundred and thirty-three Portobello Road, and - they were Roman Catholics, they were Irish, and - he - I used to meet him after school, and we used to play together, well 
on this particular day - my mother }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
aid - you - is your - you're going out to play, she said, don't go far away. And Mrs Cheetham will call you in - when it's time. Well - they were - laying wood blocks on this road then, and at the - outside our house wher
e we lived, a corner house - that was - opposite to this house - on that side, well we lived this side. Well we used to play on those steps - those were our steps you see, but on this side of the road. And we used to play there, well outside there there w
a
s a - a big bin full of sand. Well - Joey Freeman's - it was his birthday I think, 'cos it was in the summertime, it was his birthday, and - I can remember we sat on top of this bin - and - my sister started to cry, so we said, there's a policeman coming,
 
Mr Manfred's coming. And she - we put her inside and we sat on the top. Eating this pen'orth of broken biscuits, and - keep her quiet, she was nearly dead when they got her out. Yes, old Murphy came along and he said to my mother he said, I'd give her the
 
biggest tanning on her backside, he said, if I was you. My mother said, I know what to do with her. We didn't realize the danger. But that's how - the trouble - the only trouble we had with her, and right up 'til today - there was - that animosity between
 us, the youngest one of all. And she's just the same now, I had a letter from my - n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
ece this morning who lost her husband. And my sister lives at Bracknell, and this is her second husband that's already in the hospital. And that poor girl, she's only lost
 her husband a week - a fortnight - Saturday, she wrote in her letter this morning, I don't know what to do about mum, she said - she thinks I should go down there and stay with her. I mean that girl's got everything to settle up, all her husband's busine
s
s and - and everything else. And - it - the strangest think in the world - she - she's take - taken to drink as soon as she left school. She used to drink - she used to buy tuppeenny bottles of stout, and that's grown on her, she's a real alcoholic, in he
r
 letter this morning Hilda said to me - she's seventy-five now, she said, we bought mum three bottles of Guinness - and she said, and Reggie, that's her son, took mum back, and - she said, oh don't take me right home from - Basingstoke to Bracknell, she s
aid - I'll go round the pub, so that's - she said - Les - Reggie left her - his gran at the pub.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was she the only one in your family that did drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That's the only one in our family that ever drank. Oh my brother used to like - oh he thought it
 was ever so big if he had a - penny glass of four ale, he - he was a man. Bigger than anybody - in his own estimation. But my other brother didn't drink, although he worked for Buchanan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2700016\charrsid5646288 
\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s the whisky people. Used to work in their office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was there any one of your brothers or sisters that you felt you particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Any what? Oh I was very fond of my - my younger brother Sammy. But our John of course he - he was - quite - big and old to us, if you know what I mean. He was twelve years olde
r than me. But - our Sammy was our - hero. Didn't matter what - if - when he used to come home on leave, you know, they didn't get much money those days - soon as our Sammy came home we all - we all had pennies to spend and do what you like and - buy bags
 
of fruit and - chestnuts, buy chestnuts and roast them in the fender. But - our John never gave us much, he was too - high and mighty. And when his girl came to see him we had to be quiet. I know - one day, my - John - answered a - I went to answer the do
o
r - answer the bell, and my John went down you see and he pushed me at one side. So I said, I was only going to open the door. He looked at me like that, and of course in come my daughter-in-law - my sister-in-law that was - Martha, and she same in, she s
a
id, oh hello. So I didn't smile at her or anything and she went by I went - like that, so - my brother said, you do that again and I'll slap your face, and my Sammy said, you won't. There was nearly a fight on the stairs then. But we - we never had any - 
w
e never wanted to go anywhere. Our lives from Monday 'til Friday - in the home, was - always the same. And - Saturdays and Sundays - as I tell you we used to go down Portobello Road - and we used to think it was lovely if we bought fish and chips and - at
e
 it going along. Nothing could be better, and only cost a penny. And then I know - in the early evening - there used to be a man sell fish, and used - he was selling there one day, s found sixpence. And I looked round to see if anybody had lost it. Or loo
k
ing for it but they wasn't, so this man was selling this fish and there was a - I can remember it now, he got a piece of - paper, there was a haddock - and - four kippers - and a bloater, a smoked - herring, and he said, sixpence. Well I carried that home
 my dear as if I'd robbed Buckingham Palace of all its jewels. I took those home to my mum, so she said, where did you get them? I said, at - Mr Marsh was selling them on his - standing up on the stall, with the old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 naphtha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  lamp burning and he'd got all the
 fish boxes round him you see and the - us kids were standing round watching him, and we used to love to watch that, then they used to hang up - hold up - chickens, and you bid for them, and - that - that was our pleasure on the Saturday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played games at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 If you got dirty was that all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Well I don't - I don't know what my - after we'd had a - after - before we had our meals we had to wash our hands, and - when we went indoors - a
s I say we had to strip down to the waist before we went to bed or - have a bath or what have you. And - I know I went once to the - swim - swimming pool, a swimming bath down - Lancaster Road, and I went with this girl - well that was while my dad was in
 the hospital, and I went with this girl - I never forget my mum, what she - she said, do you think you - we want any more trouble, she said, your dadd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 's in the hospital, she said, I've got my arm in a sling - opening a bottle of soda water to give to dadd
y, and she was cut right across there. I can remember she had a - like a - a - little block of wood in her hand like a sort of broom handle to keep her fingers out straight, I can remember that. And she - and - and she said, and you go - I said I was only
 
watching, I didn't get in the water. She said, no, she said, you could have fallen in the water and been dead, then what I would - what would I have done? Of course then I realized you know that - we shouldn't disobey her. But of course children of today,
 
if I told them that - if I were to tell that to my grandchildren they'd laugh at me. Say fancy - fancy you - fancy our grandmother - great-grandmother being like that, they - they'd look at me and laugh, but that's how we were bought up and we're none the
 worse for it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have any hobbies in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Any hobbies? No, we - oh - we had a parrot, and - window box, the other time - in my box I had - mignonette, and - mignonette and two daffodil bulbs at Christmas, that we grew for my mum, an
d these daffodils bulbs were put in a pickle jar - and then when we saw this flower come out oh we thought that was wonderful. That's all we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have any other pets?
