g plaits, and if he could catch me he'd hang onto these plaits and one day - I'd just about had enough of it and - straight - I hit him in the nose and I could see his nose bleed. I - oh I went home to my mother and I thought I'd killed him. And - whateve
r
 was that boy's name? Dominic something. Ever after that we were friends. He'd got a sister, she was blind. We were friendly with her but we could never stand this boy. He was a Roman Catholic. But - after - ever after that when once I stood up for myself
,
 that - that was the end of it I know my Sammy come after him one day - he said, I'll break your neck, he said, if you pull my sister's hair again. But - he was a lot older than us. But - he used to take his sister to church. He was kind to her, but I thi
n
k it was just out of devilment more than anything else. No real spite. I never had - as long as I can look back - I've never had any - animosity - or hatred against anyone. Because - we were bought up - that - there's a reason in everything you do. If - i
f
 - if a child is blind or an imbecile - that's the way God meant it to be. And it's our place to help them, that's what my mum used to tell us. If you see an old person wanting to cross the road or a blind person, you take their hand and take them across 
t
he road. And - when there was a - little girl run over by the side - that lived next door but one to us - there was a - there was a reason that it happened, and we were taught that there - there - there must be a reason for everything to happen, and then 
