d
 - the lids were fixed on, of course - I - wrote it different to what I'm saying it now, but this is what it meant. And then I said they were all parked - all put into a place together to be taken to - places - and they never saw - never met anymore. And 
I said they - were taken and placed at the corners of the street, and painted red with - our Queen's initials on. And that was the - life of a pillar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 box, and where I got that from I don't know, it was quite original. And ever since then - I always had an idea I wanted to write.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You do write don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? Yes. But - I always wanted to do it in a big way. Now - when I was seventeen - or sixteen - this Madam Collier that I told you about, I used to write all her - writer all her - all her lette
rs - and - answer all her - her - answer all her letters, I was - I must have been about sixteen or seven - seventeen, I'd left the Post Office anyway. And - my husband - of course he wasn't my husband then, he used to come in - and - he - she used to all
o
w - allow him to come in and she had a - one servant, Mary, and - she he - he used to come in there and - do little odd jobs for her like - clean the brass so something like that. And - Mary, she was an old woman, but - we used to call her Aunty Mary. And
 
then I used to do - do all the writing, then my - she used to give my husband the letters to post, always trusted him to post the letters at night. Anyway - she had one son. And he went out to Purn and Bucoe - in Brazil, and she tried - they had a baby, h
e
r son was married - and had a - had - they had this first baby, and he went out on this - to work out in Brazil, he was something to do with the - railway - and - they tried all they possibly could for me to go with them. And - my - my mother came down an
d
 spoke to them all about it and - she said, no - she wouldn't - wouldn't dream of it for - a - allowing me to go. Of course I wanted to go, I thought that was going to be wonderful. And then - my father was talking to me one day and my Sammy was home, and
 
he said, if you go out there - he said, you'll never come home to England, never see your mother anymore. Well that did it. 'Cos I thought you could come home on the tuppeny tube. So I said, no, I - I won't go, but she wanted me to go out there as a - sor
t
 of - companion, she spoke several languages and so did he, he was a very clever man. He was - a designer, you know what I mean, a - of all these things. Not an architect you wouldn't call him but - he used to design all sorts of things, very very clever 
h
e was, that was her only - only son, very very nice man he was, and I loved the wife too, she was very sweet. She - had been a nurse - nursing sister or something. But she dearly wanted me to go out there with them and I thought that would be lovely but -
 if I could come home weekends well of course -
