\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we never had any more canings then, no, and the 
teachers never had a cane, we had cardboard - pointers. They were a - a roll of cardboard and they had like red handles, and that's what we - she used to point on the board, that was all stopped then, because that - that girl was crippled through that cut
. And - of course it was an accident, I mean she didn't mean to hit her like that but she was so spiteful. Well after that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, never bothered. And then the - the School Board man went round to the granny and told her that - she'd stayed away from sc
hool, and I know they said if she stayed away from school her mother would have to pay five shillings. You have to go before the School}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288  Board. But - oh she was a - oh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  she was a poor little thing. I know she came to one of my - parties once, a - a children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s party, and she says, I wish I had a mum like you and a daddy. I said - I said, well he can be your daddy I said, if you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  if}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
you come round, I'll ask my daddy if he'll be your dad as well. She'd come to our}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
house very often after that, she used to come to Sunday school with us there. We used to say to the - ask your mummy can you come home and have tea with us and - she often did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How many teachers were there at your school, about five or six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? How many what? Teachers? Let's see now, le
t me see. Teacher Rover was the first class. That was when you come out of the infants, Miss - her name was Rhoda, but we used to call her teacher Rover. Miss Ro - Rhoda something her name was, teacher Rhoda. Mrs Springer. Two sisters Hallett. Miss Reid. 
M
rs Wilson was the infants teacher. I think there was - six - six teachers and a - and a headmistress, and then - but - no teacher - went to another class to teach. That teacher that took, us took everything. Prayers - assembly in the morning and in the ha
l
l, and - then we - we - we would go in and - perhaps it was sums - geography - geography - then it would be lunchtime, we'd - you - you go out to play in the meantime, between the two lessons, and then - you'd come home at twelve and you went back to scho
ol quarter to two. You had to be in - assembly. And - then - but sometimes we used to - go back straight to class, it all depended. And - then there'd be afternoon c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ll, your names'd be called out, the register would be called. And then - perhaps we'd have 
what we called science lesson. And - history. And then - one - all one afternoon we would have needlework and knitting. In the morning we'd have scripture. And drill. We'd go out in the play ground for drill, we used to call it, exercise. And - well that 
- that's how it went all through the - Wednesdays was always essays. And - scripture in the - scripture stories in the morning. And drill. And the afternoon it was - essays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of drill was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You - had to write - transcription one day, and dictation the next. And to write}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
a short story. And - that's what I used to love. And - always - and Friday afternoons from playtime - it was always spelling bee, you all had to get round the class, and the teacher would ask you to spell, if you could
n't spell anything - you had to sit down. If you spelt it wrongly you had to sit down. Well the last one that - last one that was left used to get sixpence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 They actually gave you money for this did they as a prize?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, yes, every Friday - 
every Friday those that spelt the best - the best was sixpence but - if it was a tie you got a - a silver three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 penny bit each.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever win?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, of course I did. Ever so many times, I was very fortunate, they said, she - she only asks y
ou to spell the words you know. Well she didn't, I've always been - excellent at spelling but I don't know about these big words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you first went to school your mother took you to begin with did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How long did that go on for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh not long because - next door to ours - next door to us lived the Stags, and opposite - to us lived some children named Finch, we always used to go to school arm in arm. And then wait - and wait to - come home - and then - always at - when I used 
to come out after - having my dinner as we called it, used to come out there used to be three or four of them waiting for me on the step, we used to come - arm in arm back to school, and of course - it's only while I was in the infants school that mum too
k me at the beginning. Until my sister was old enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How long did it take you to get to school? About five minutes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 About - mm. Five minutes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And you came home for your midday meals in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Came home - yes, sometimes we'd
 - see each other home, sometimes we'd go to the corner of the road - continuation of Chesterton Road where - Cissy Buckingham lived, and we'd - go up and see her indoors first, or we'd knock at the door and ask if - if - if she was all right and - then s
h
e'd say, oh don't - don't tell my gran I haven't been to school. Well we didn't. Naturally. We only had another girl then, Maude Sexton, her father - her people kept a dairy up there, and she was a madam. She wouldn't associate with any of us, her father 
k
ept the shop, and - she went to music lessons, sixpence a time. And - she was there -- she used to play - play the piano for the marching, when we were drilling in - if it was raining - we had drill in the hall, so of course we used to do a sort of a - se
t dance sort of thing if you know what I mean, not real dancing but exercising t the - and she used to play the piano. I used to pull her hair as I went by.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 It was a Board School wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, School Board for London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it nine 'til four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
We used to go in the morning - a quarter to nine 'til twelve. And - a quarter to two 'til four, if you were in the lower classes, half past four if - you got up to standard six. And - a quarter to five - or five o'clock if you were in the ex-seventh.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So it was quite a long day towards the end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. And we used to have a - ten minutes play in the morning. And a quarter of an hour in the afternoon for the big girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have a playing field or just a yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No, nothin
g only - two - very big playgrounds. It wasn't until I was leaving school that we had a net - netball, you know, this - but I was leaving school when they erected those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you play rounders and things in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we never - no, never di
d anything of that, was all a stone - playground, but - we used to have - do - exercises - out there and - then we used to have - in the summer - we'd sit out there and sing songs - There'll always be an England and - and - God Save the Queen and all that
 sort of thing. And - but we made our own amusement. We used to play touch and hopscotch - and then old Mr Ivy, he was the school cleaner - if he found out who did the chalking, he used to report us. You see? So - nobody ever split on anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did the teachers particularly emphasise, did they have a very strong regard for things like manners or tidiness or punctuality?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh my dear, yes. You - you - that's - my mother used to send us to school with a - I can see my mum now, twelve o'clock at ni
ght - ironing and goffering our pinafores, white started pinafores, every day - we had a clean pinafore on. And my - hair was always - right down - I could sit on it right down in two big plaits with a fringe. But - I know once or twice I went to school w
i
th a - all loose and my teacher said - you mustn't come to school with your hair like that Suzie, she said, because some of the children are not too clean, and she, said, I wouldn't like you to catch anything, like that. And poor Cissy Stag, she come to s
chool, she was - absolutely sent down to the cleansing station, it was a shame though. Because - I mean she was dirty. But there you are, you - you meet them don't you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Inside the school did it form into little groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What three or four kids together? Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was anybody ever left out on their own, you know, that nobody ever played with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, only little Cissy Buckingham 'til - because they - they said - she - she's never had a dad. She - she - of course she was illegitimate you see. A
nd - well those days that was terrible. She was absolutely crushed that girl, and yet - she was - one of the cleverest kids - she did the most remarkable drawing and painting. Oh we used to have painting lessons. Paint maps, draw maps and paint them diffe
r
ent colours. That was what we called science afternoon, sometimes we'd have - all sorts of test you know and - learn - we - physiology, learn about - that's when we got up in the higher classes, first aid, you - if anybody fainted and - what to do if - if
 - anybody fell, always pull their limbs out straight and never move them and - oh we - I used to love that too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents show much interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, of course they did. Had to - take a school report home, poor Cissy Bu
ckingham never took hers home. She always lost it. Oh she had a sad life that girl. Yet she was brilliant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What happened to her afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 She went to work - she went to work at Bradley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2359735\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s - sewing, first of all she went there picking up pins an
d running errands and then - she was on the machine, working the machine. And the last that we heard of her, after the mother died and the granny died - she was - staying with some people, and - she was a dress designer. Yes. Yes, she finished up well. Bu
t oh she had a dog's life at school. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were there many others like her there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we had another little girl there, Ada Beller, she was a little - sick girl she was never well, but - she - wouldn't go out to play in case anybody punched her, an
d - I think she died when she was thirteen - with TB. That was another only child but she did have a - she did have a dad, only poor Cissy we knew never had any dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say some girls had dirty hair?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say some of the children were quite dirty in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, my dear, the old nurse was there - in - and they used to put oil of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 sassafras}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  on your hair. I can see that - see them - now, the - poor kids, and you keep a mile away from them. Poor Cissy Stag always reeked of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did the school tend to divide between those who were clean and those who were dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, yes, oh yes, you had to have that. And - we had to - when we got into school, we had to take our own duster, dust our seats and dust our desks 'cos 
you sat two in a desk, and - little inkwell each end. And - I suppose there was about - about thirty in a class then. But of course they were - as - as we got up into the higher class the - seventh and ex-seventh were mixed - we - oh I suppose about forty
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it boys and girls altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? No. Boys - school was right the other side. Then there was the infants school, that was separate, and then there was the big girls school, oh it was an enormous school. But of course it's all new - newl
y built now. It - it faces - you can see it from that road, up at the top. No, we never - going to school and - right until - we were - grown up we never went the other side of the station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What did the teachers think about things like manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? Not - manners? You had to - had to get up and answer - open the door for your teacher as she came in and out, and - always say please and thank you. And always when we - in the morning we'd go in and sit on our desks and - as our teacher came in w
e all stand up and said good morning Miss Reid, and as we used to go home in the evening, good - good night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 hey expect you to speak the Quee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 n's English and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, of course - of course you did, you didn't have to say ain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
t and all that sort of thing. And sound your aitches. No, it's - I speak worse now but of course of this impediment, that's - than what I did then, because I - I had a very good voice for singing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents every visit the school very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh the - the - come to the school? On parents day? Oh yes. They'd come come in and see all the - all the - patchwork and needlework that we did but of course - we - we had to make patches at home, and darning. Darn our socks and stockings. Knit socks, w
e had to knit socks. Knit perhaps the heel of a sock and it would be on a card with your name on it and how many marks you had. OH yes, we all - we had all that to do, but I could never crochet. Knit, yes, I could knit everything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have things like school choirs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have much music in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Much what? No - we only used to - oh yes, we used to have a - have a singing lessons - sing old English songs, and - there used to be - harmonizing we used to sing A bow to boat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
race in the ferry, and - we would harmonise, I was alto, and - Ada Beller, that little girl that was so delicate, she had a beautiful singing voice, and - she used to sing alone sometimes but - and then there was - about a dozen girls - other - you 
know, used to sing otherwise, tenor or whatever you call it, I don't remember. But - yes, we had our singing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
lessons. Piano lessons if you had a piano and you could pay sixpence a time but - that never came - and the funny thing - my boy was three years ol
d - and he'd been very ill - and - he came out of the hospital, he was in there about six months, had whooping cough, pneumonia - and - I think it was rheumatic fever, rheumatism, well he was in Kensington Infirmary there, he was in there a long long time
,
 and he was so think when he came out he couldn't walk, oh no, he was four, four or five - was just before he went to school, and - he was so thin - and his - well I - when I bought him some shoes - we could get them on and off without lacing - they were 
little boots with four holes, you could untie them and - and get them off without undoing them. Oh he went to a living skeleton. Enteritis he had. And - he went away}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 down to - John Hall Edwards Convalescent Home, and while he was down there smallpox broke o
ut and I had to meet him and the nurse at - at - Edgeware Road Station - Marylebone Station, and - he - wasn't allowed to come home and he went down to - a Nurse Parks - down in Norfolk. Six of them went, and - she looked after them down there. And - then
 
I - my husband and I went to meet him. And we had to - no, we had to go to the hospital, that was right, they were taken back to the hospital and - it - me and my - my husband went to meet him, he wouldn't come to us. He said, I want my dear one. He would
n
't come to us. Well he was so thin, - we - I used to take him out in the push chair and he used to say, mummy, will you - will you take me down the back turnings don't - don't let - don't let the kids see me in this pram. 'Cos he couldn't walk. You ought 
t
o see him now, he's taller than me and - he's huge. And - it's only - of course since he's come home from Africa he's put on a lot of weight. Anyway - this - we had him home, well then I had to feed him on - I had to buy - fish heads, cods head - and stew
 
them - clean them and stew them and strain - the liquor off, and then I used to go to the butchers, Frosts that was down here, and I used to get - fish feet - chickens feet, I had to scrub them and - put them in boiling water and scrub them, and - then pu
t
 them in a stone jar and 'course we had a fire oven, not what we've got now, and - they used to be in there - stewing all day, then at night I'd strain that off, and I had to feed him with that to make a new coating to his guts. All the coating of his sto
m
ach came off. And - after that - he had pneumonia, and I was giving him cold liver oil and malt, and one day - I went to give him his milk, and I put the sugar in it with the cod liver oil spoon, and that child never stopped vomiting and to this day - 'co
u
rse he's had his tonsils out since, but - to this day - he could - he would - if you gave him - well I don't know now he's married but - even when he come home from Africa - he'd always smell that spoon. But - they were very very kind to him, but - he - h
e gradually got on. But it's a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you were at school do you remember if there were any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He went to the school round here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were there any gangs as such in your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Any what? Oh there used to be - what, boys and girls gangs tog
ether? OH yes, there would be - the naughty ones my mum used to call 'em. Yes, they used to go - go in Boots and Woolworth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s and pinch things, like they do now. These kids upstairs - two children came here - waiting for that big boy, twelve, he's a little 
beast, and - that lady downstairs had just cleaned all her place out and she - she - cleans it and sweeps the dustbin and polished the lids and everything, she's cleaning mad, well they stole a pot of jam, and after she'd cleaned all down there, they smas
h
ed it on here and - dropped it all on her mat that was out there drying. So I saw them do it you see. So I went out to them. And - I told Mrs Lebbins, I said, it wasn't your kids, I said, it was that boy that comes for - for - for - this other boy, well h
e's twelve years old and - oh - he - if he dare he'd hit me. I spoke to him yesterday. I said, upstairs or out. I said, and don't look at me like that, I said, you're nothing, you're not important to me, I said to his father this morning. I said, no child
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 re}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
n's important to me, I said, not eve my own, I said, until they go out and earn their own living, then, I said, I look up to them, but until then, I said, they're under my supervision, they've got to do as they're told, and I saw they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So you kept away from these groups at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh we never had a - chance to go with them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were there gangs inside the school itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, they were boys about - twelve or thirteen I suppose but - when they went out to - when they - they - whe
n they were about fourteen they were paperboys and - they'd got jobs with a milkman and that, it all seemed to fade away, we never had any trouble, not like there is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Did I like school? Oh yes. Yes, I hated it be
ing away. But I was very unfortunate at school. I only had one medal but - it - if - if you were regular attendance for - for three years you got a bronze medal. I got two - well they weren't silver - silver plated medals, but I had a prize every - about 
f
ive prizes for regular attendance, but - I never filled the full year in. Because - I - only through illness. But apart from that I never - I - I never had any - reason to be home, only through illness, but - only when my daddy was in the hospital - I had
 to stay home and - look after my two little sisters while my mum went to the hospital with him in the van. That's the only -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 After you'd been in the ex-seventh you went to Southend Technical school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No, I went to - I went in - into the -
 I went down to - stay with my aunt. And I had to finish school down there - the end of the high street, the technical school, there - there wasn't any - schools like there are now. You had to - I went to Paddington Tech. First. And then when I was ill - 
I had this - this rheumatism, and - I went down - to stay with my aunt, then I came back again and - and - I did write it all down, the dates, when I had scarlet fever, rheumatism, scarlet fever, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  and - started with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 This was in your last year at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
A lot of children had that, and scarlet fever, and then it - of course it left me with all this rheumatism. No - nobody ever noticed about that hand, nobody - never remarked on it, but of course now the blood - won't run throu
gh the veins, that's why I'm getting - that's why I'm so afraid if I were to cut myself or anything you see, because it - the vein - of course I've got ever so much thinner. I've gone from eleven stone to eight stone six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Just recently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 In that 
photograph of me in the office I weighed - nearly eleven stone. But of course I was tall with it you see, it didn't show. But - during the time now since - since 1958 - until 1966 I was - been in the hospital - eight times. And if I call my doctor in with
 these legs as they are he'd send me in now, well I wouldn't go. I wouldn't - I wouldn't go in that hospital again if - unless I was - had - absolutely helpless.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Would you have wanted to have stayed on at school if you'd have had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? What?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Could you have gone on to another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Could have gone back to school afterwards, no, I went in the - I went - in a - a Post Office Savings Bank and - and it was from there that I got this - illness because - the st
rangest thing was this, my eldest brother had six children. Oh he had four then. Well - I was taken - and I hadn't seen those children for weeks. I went into the hospital with this scarlet fever - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 , that was the first thing, and scarlet fever
 followed. I - and - I know they lanced my throat from the inside, they - it started with the - quinseys then and then it - they said it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 , then I was kept in a side ward, Western Fever Hospital, Fulham. And I'd only been in there two days and
 they bought - my brother's eldest girl in. Two days later, in the same ward, but I was in the side ward, they bought - two more in, a girl and a boy - and - about five days after that they bought my brother in. And he nearly died. And as they sent him to
 - convalescent home - I was in the hospital 'til they'd all gone home, before they sent me even convalescent, because I'd got - rheumatic fever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did it cost money in those days to be in hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. No. Anyway - only for your doctor. And - used
 to be a shilling - if you were a - a child and one and six if you were grown up. And the - then the - doctor used to make your medicine up in the - doctor Rennie's daughter used to live in the top part of one of those houses, and she had a surgery - up h
e
re. But she was a - specialist in Charing Cross Hospital as well. But - she had a partner that used to be with her. But that was the funniest thing out, we all - how we were all taken there and I hadn't seen them for weeks and weeks. Because then he moved
 down to - down to - Wimbledon, and of course that's where he died, he's buried in Nelsons old churchyard, Wimbledon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was there a lot of illness around in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? At that time, oh yes - scarlet feber and - that's when they first broug
ht out these injections. A lot of illness. And of course that - that left me ill for a long long time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You definitely think you benefited from attending school anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? What in these hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 In just the ordinary school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh y
es, yes. Yes, you - you had to be polite and never - never answer back and never - I - I know one - a - girl came in there one day, and she bought a goldfish, up in Golden Road and she bought it in and put it under her desk, and we were all standing looki
n
g at it. And the teacher came in and she said, sit down. But - none of us took any notice. So she banged on the table, on her desk. She used to sit on a high desk like - they had in these - tennis - places, tennis courts, you know where they sit up on tha
t high desk thing, and - she was a new teacher we had there, a temporary teacher, and - she said - what are you looking at? Anyway this girl brought this little - this little tiny goldfish in a jam jar, she bought it - I think it was three}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 pence, anyway it died - just after it - she bought it for her little brother. They used to sell - bird food - seed and - bird seed and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  carr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 y }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 away seeds and herbs and all up in Golbourne Road, goldfish - and - fishing rods and - fish bait. I know we used to see the worms 
wriggling - in a - in a tank, eeh. I know we were sitting one day - I never liked winkles and there's a - my - my sisters used to gorge them, we're sitting - they were sitting eating these winkles one day and it nearly made me sick, and I said to my siste
r, do you know what they are? I said, you know - you know what's up in Golbourne Road, up at Clarke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s? So she said, yes. Well I said, that's them without any shells on. Sick. Oh dear. No, when I'm here alone, I live it all over again. I - we were poor - but
 we were never hungry, we never wanted - for anything, because we had no ambition to be rich - no ambition for - only to get on and to love our mum and dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You were talking about these rich women in Westbourne Park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Westbourne Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever have to curtsey and things like that to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did what? No, only to a lady that used to come there, she was - a - whatever was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  name, Lady Montague. My mother went several times to her house, 29 Pembridge Gardens she had a house, a
nd then they moved into a big place somewhere else, and my - they were Jews, and - she - we - what - what - only just used to nod to them as they went by but we used to think they were all princesses - 'cos they all had - not exactly crinoline but bustles
 
you know, beautiful dresses, but - I never wanted to be dressed like that. No. All I - all I wanted to - all I wanted to wear was a - was - a - navy blue bloomers and - and a blouse. I - I - and to run about without a skirt. I always wanted that as a kid.
 
And of course those days you - that wasn't allowed. But then at school - suddenly I - I don't know why it was, we all had to take - take our slips off, and we had blouse and - - these navy blue bloomers, oh I was queen of the earth then my dear. When we w
ere allowed to do that. Yes, so -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When people talk about life in Edwardian England they talk about a different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is what dear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 They talk about the different groups that were in those days, different classes and things, did you ever think of 
yourself as belonging to one particular group or class at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 A group of what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever think of yourself as belonging to a particular class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No my dear, we were the rich and the poor, there were no between. The - the - most of 
the girls that - I went to school with - when they were fourteen they were packed off into - with a - with your little basket, two of everything and they went into gentleman's service. We never got that far. We never did that, we - my sister served in the
 
greengrocers, and - the other sister - oh she served in another shop or one or two shops and - well - I was just in the Post Office and - I - I worked - did writing for Madam Collier, I worked in - that - Savings Bank and then I went down to live with the
se - people, these Germans. And I got married from there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of class did they come from, the Germans?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He was a - a - tobacco merchant from Havana, and he'd got - children at Stuttgart - in - in a college there, and two younger children - 
in a - in Havana, and these two elder children - three elder children were brought up by their aunt, and - then they moved to England, they bought a big house called Clovelly on the Lees at Westcliffe, and through Madam Collier I was introduced to them, a
n
d - I went down there and - lived with them, and - taught them as - much about English as I could, you know the ways and - of - shopping, and - oh - and then my - of course my husband - he wasn't my husband then, he gave his job and he came down there, an
d
 he took a job as a milkman, much to his parents disgust, and - we got married then, from there. And I sent him home with the marriage lines, I didn't come home. And - he work - he worked down there and then of course the - we - came back to London when m
y
 daughter was two, and - 'course the war broke out, she was two years old and the war broke out and of course from then - I worked on munitions and - round at Clement Talbot's on their - aeronautical statistics I was - doing that. Sometime I was there and
 then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What were you doing while you were at Clement Talbot's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
What? Clement Talbot's? Oh it was all figure work, all - all - all sorts of work. I got shut in there one night. Over in the - bond - what they call the bond is where they kept all 
platinum - and - all different things and it was a - iron room, right over - on the railway, well on this Sunday, we were in there stocktaking - well a girl I worked with, Edie Liffingwell, I'll never forget that girl - we were working over there with - M
r
 Bond on the bond, and - he went off early, we had our lunch there, we didn't come out - of the building at all, you were searched when you went in, you were searched when you came out. 'Cos there was all platinum and all sorts of bits of stuff - over the
r
e in this iron room. Well - Mr Bond left us, he said, you two all be all right. So we said, yes. It was in the wintertime and it was half past five, so - as we went into the little slip room - of course the big iron room was all locked up, and there was t
h
e anti-room where you hung your clothes up, and a wash basin and that, well - I hung - my coat on the back of the door, Edie hung hers over a back of a chair. So she said, my Frank's coming up for - to meet me. I was living in Chesterton Road then, they w
e
re looking after my little girl. Of course my husband was abroad. And - with his father, in France, so - I said, oh well I'll be all right. Anyway - I heard the door shut, she thought I'd gone home, because - I heard the outer door shut - well - the momen
t
 that that was shut all the electricity was turned off - from the gate, and the - telephone was closed down, you see. And I was in there 'til half past eight at night, 'til the night watchman came on. With his dog. I said, I would have died of fright. Any
w
ay when - Mr Masters his name was, he come round with - his dog, old Nell, and - I called out. Well I frightened the life out of him I think, anyway he rang the man from the gate. And he phoned the police, and - from - Ladbroke Grove police - Nottingdale 
p
olice station two policemen came, and - got me out and I had to see - my boss - the next morning. He sent me home for a week, he said the shock. But of course poor Edie she thought I'd gone, she thought she was the last one out. But I would have been ther
e 'til the morning and - if it hadn't been for that dog. And of course my mother-in-law, she was having fifty fits, she wondered what had happened to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get the original job with the Post Office, who got you that?
