\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s, and - and I moved into Chesterton Road, we - we both - we went on mum - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 am}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 munit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ons and then - I don't know ho
w it was, but I had a letter - and asked me if I would go for an interview at Gloucester Terrace, they took over a house and it was to do with diseased - soldiers and sailors - effects you know. And I could - and I was - I was there until my husband came 
h
ome from the war, and he made me leave because his - friends mother had this sweet shop and confectioners, a lovely shop, we did well there, and - I worked there until the shop was sold. The lease run out and the shop was sold, and we moved out of the hou
s
e in Portobello Road, up to this house up here, 297 Portobello Road, and I lived there twenty years. And - my daughter was ten - when my son was born. She was ten years olf when my son was born. And he was eighteen months old when I went to the hospital, 
in 1923 and I was there 'til 1943 January. And then - June - I left there and in June I went - they paid me up 'til June, and in June - I went up to - the Associated British Cinemas, and -
