\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did they ever go out together, in the evenings or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, I told you yesterday they - they - very very seldom went out unless it was - unless my dad would - go with mum if she went up to Pic
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 adilly where she used to do cooking and Berkele
y Square, or - Holland Park Avenue, and - Camden Hill Terrace - Camden Hill Gardens my mum used to cook - for up there, people that lived up there and Monte - Montefuries lived up there, their - their name was Franklin, and then - I know the elder man die
d
 and then there was Lord Montefury - the daughter was - was - Mrs Macato, and - mum - my mum used to cook there. And - if - mum had to go there for an interview, dad used to go with her, but not after his - not after he was at - accident, he didn't go - h
e - he didn't go hardly anywhere.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Before he had his accident what time did he come home in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Mm. Well apart from that - apart from that - I can never - I can never remember my dad ever going out unless he took us children. If he - if
 he'd come home - I suppose it was about half past five or six o'clock, I'd meet him at the station - and walk home with him and he'd buy his Evening News, tuck it under his arm and we'd walk home, he'd have a wash and have his dinner. And - sometimes he'
d
 sit and read the paper and - we'd go down in our little room to play, and - but we never - never in the wintertime, we were home from school, we never were allowed out. And it was - in the wintertime I was going down to meet my dad I said - to my mum, ca
n
 I go and meet - meet my dad and tell him what you said, because that was when I had carried me boots to school, so I thought I'd be the first to tell home. My dad put his arm round me, he never said anything. I - I said, mummy's very cross with me. So he
 
said, why? I said - he knew - I said, because, I said Mr Rogers mended my boots and I wouldn't wear them. I wanted new ones. He said, well, he said, you won't have new ones, you'll wear those boots or you'll go to school with no boots or shoes or stocking
s
 on at all. So that was the punishment. He wouldn't have bought me a pair of shoes if he was worth a hundred pounds. So - I had to wear them. But - anyway - when - when we had new - new ones bought - I had just the ones I wanted. I looked at my sister lik
e that. I said, you've got what mum chose for you and I've got mine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was that Kit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I was always a winner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your father ever belong to any savings club do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Have I got any savings? No. My - there was nothing - left - when my 
dad died. I don't even - know if he was insured. Oh no, no, when my father died I - I paid for his funeral, I've got the bill at - bill in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He didn't attend any clubs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes, because I was - when my father died I - I was at the shop down in Portobello Road.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When your father was ill, when he had the operation and your mother went out to cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I can't hear you dear, it's no good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When your father had his operation and your mother went out cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was it the Cheethams who looked after you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Nobody else came in at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, we never had anybody else, no, who - who'd come and look after kids those days? You want to read that little poem, that'll tell you what - we - no - nobody's
 come in and make us a cup of tea. Well, that was our fault. No, nobody - and I know that if we went out to a party my mother used to want to know where we were going - and - who the people were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Can you remember your mother ever being ill at all when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? No, only - I can remember - that - I can remember my mother fainting. And - I went in the room, it was in the evening and my dad was - was bathing her - bathing her head with a wet flannel. And I screamed, I thought s
he was dead. And - he said - the doctor's coming to - tomorrow to mummy, he said, you mustn't worry her. So he said - you children must wash up the breakfast things before you go to school. So - oh we made our beds and washed up the breakfast things and p
ut the knives and forks on the table for dinnertime, but - it was - mum fainted, it was her change of life they said. But - that's the only time - I never remember - never remember my mother - being in bed for a day's illness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Can you remember when one of your little sisters was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Can you remember what happened when one of your sisters was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I can re - I can - remember - my Kit being born, but - she was born - in Telford Road, 7 Telford Road. Yes, I know my mother had a 
- had the - I had the - the - we had the nurses in because - Doctor Redding came. He was a young doctor then. And his daughter took over. But I can never remember my mother being in bed. I know when - when my Kit was born I can remember looking over the c
o
t to see her, and - well - she was in a cradle, you know, wicker cradle thing what they had those days. And we said, we wonder how mummy got her. And looked down on her. And my May, my - middle sister, she was a lovely person, my Phyl was like her - she s
a
id, we didn't want her did we? She said I want - I wanted my mum and you wanted our dad didn't you? I said, yes, well I said, no, we didn't want her. And we never wanted her and we never wanted her to the end because she was a bitch, she turned out - the 
only quarrel - my mum and dad had was over her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh - she was - that was a real - a real quarrel, I was married. And - I can remember my mother going and staying with - with my Kit and my dad was alone, and my husband went - and my
 dad came to our place to dinner on that Sunday. That was when I lived in Chesterton Road. But - of course and mum went down to - down to my - went down to - to my brother's - oh no, I was down at the shop I remember. It - it's - going over all these thin
g
s I - one thing comes up before the other. You see, when - when I write these things down - I can remember exactly. No, I can never - never remember see - never remember my - mum being in bed. But I know - I know the baby - was born there because we had a
 
Mrs - Archway - Archer, Archer, that came in - and - looked after - looked after my mum and did the washing, and I know - she - I can remember her saying to - somebody - when I do this washing - I always have half a quarter of gin. I can remember that now
. Yet I can never remember my mother being in - in bed with my sister, and I can remember - all the baby clothes and - handing on a little clothes horse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents have many friends coming in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did they have many friends? Not - nobody came 
to our house. Nobody came to our house, only - that lady from - who - came from - Brassey's, she was their nurse and then she was a lady's maid. She was with them for donkey's years. And she used to come occasionally to see us. But - no, we - we never had
 
any friends, only an old lady, Mrs Birch used to come from the work house, every - about once a month she used to come to Sunday dinner, and - then my mum used to give her a bag of cakes to take home and pay her fare back, was only tuppence each way, and 
- I can remember my dad seeing her on the bus. But - yes, poor old granny Birch, she used to come with a poke bonnet and a grey shawl. And I can remember her knitting my mum a tea cosy. It's a - a blue and white tea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 cosy, I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents ever go out to visit neighbours at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, I told you that yesterday, no, they never went out anywhere, if - the only time that they ever went out together - was if - 
mum was working late, my dad would go and meet her, and - sometimes they - used to go out shopping together, but after my dad's - accident or whatever it was that caused it, he - we - I can never remember them going out together. We was always at home and
 - dad was always at - at home with us in the evenings when mum was out, and - and Mr and Mrs - Mr and Mrs Cheetham used to be in their room or sometimes they'd be in with us, it all depended.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you ever remember being told to call certain people sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember being told to call certain people sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, only - only - old Mrs Hilbury, this lady up here, we call her - we called her - ma'am, that's all, yes ma'am and no ma'am, three bags full ma'am, we said when we come out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
That was a lady that - I was tossed over the wall - when - coming back from her house. When my brother and I were sent up to take a message.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What happened then, is that the horse thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And - that's all I know, 
and when - and - when - when - and when - they had a ball - at - at Brassey's, I know I had a - I had a grey velvet frock with a white - coll - collar, and white - white shoes and socks. No, patent shoes and white socks. I can remember that, and a great b
ig bow on my hair, and - after the dinner was over or whatever it was there were dancing, and all round was like a theatre, and the servants were allowed all up there to watch the dancing. And I had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  ice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
cream, oh, and a big silver spoon, I thought I was in - Buckingham Palace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is that where your mother worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 That was the only time - no, I never remember calling anybody sir or madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who would be considered the most important people round here?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 In those days, not now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, only our doctor. Doctor Redding and - and - Doctor Hislop. They - they were - they were the only - only people, 'cos Doctor Redding was very very - aristocratic, used to war a top hat, and a - beautiful spoken, and - that's all - we never ha
d any occasion to - all - always at school we used to call our headmistress yes ma'am, and no ma'am, that's all. But Mrs Wilson, we used to say yes Mrs Wilson and no Mrs Wilson, she was the infants teacher, but - not, I don't remember - anybody around her
e.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about the viar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh the old Rev we used to call him. Yes, Father Dennison. Father Dennison, Father Tearks, Father Bright, Father George. Father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he belong to the reich class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 They're - different because it followed on over 
there but Father Dennison was very old, he used to - walk with a stick. I must write and ask the vicar - how long that church has been built, I must write him a - a line, and - get Mrs - whats her name to leave it in the letterbox, unless I see him and ca
ll him over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about the shopkeepers, what kind of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh, they used to be - now - when we lived in Portobello Road there was a row of shops. The corner - was the barbers, Mr Reid, next door to that was the ice cream - shop, and 
they had machines in there and - if my mother thought we went in there we'd get a broken neck. And - they used to put a penny in the slot and win money, and we used to stand looking in the window, and they sold ice cream and cakes, and - lemonade and that
 sort of thing, that was Charlie Rears, and he had a - he used to send out - all these men out with ice cream - barrows, you know, they were all Italians. Next door to that was Miss Drew. She sold second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 hand furniture. Next door to that was Sallow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s the bakers. Next door to that was Mrs Hay - Hayward who had the paper shop, Miss Hayward who had the paper shop. Next door to that was Turn - Turni}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ses was the fish shop but that was opposite. Oh next door to that was - was - Cripps, Mrs Cripps and she had two d
aughters, Grace and Ivy, next door to that was - what was her name, Yonkins or Jonkins, and they - we used to laugh because they had a - lavatory pan in the window and a bath and we used to think that was ever so funny, we had - I always hoped I'd go in a
n
d sit on that and have - and sit on that and have - and they could see me through - through the window. And - they were - builders and decorators and they kept the barrow inside you know, and round into the mews they kept - trucks, you know, what they sen
t out the men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 with the ladders and things on, and then at the corner - was - a - a woman and she kept}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 - she sold tea and - cups of tea and sugar and cigarettes and - and - well sort of a cafe, no sit down but - you could go in there and buy a cup of tea, th
e - workmen used to go in there and buy cups of tea. Then there was the mews the other entrance to the mews, which is now all knocked down. And then on the opposite side was a greengrocers named Amsteds, well then - we lived next door but one to that. Llo
y
ds lived in their own house here and then we lived in the next house to that in Mrs Green's house. I can remember that as plain as could be and on the opposite side of the road - there was the - old Mr and Mrs Crump, they used to sell - stale biscuits - a
n
d stale bread, if we ever bought a loaf from them my mum would make you take it back, because we used to get a bit of iced cake for a - for a - a makeweight, and next door to that was the - Dukes Motto, a little - off license, next door to that was the fr
ied fish shop, and then there was a row of houses that led onto Murchison Road, and the rest part of that was Portobello Road that finished up - the next house we moved into. When Mr Green died Mrs Green went back to Wales.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Mrs Green was your landlady was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
She was the landlady, yes. Only - he was an engine driver, old Mr Green, and he died, a great big fat man he was, and he died and Mrs Green went back to Wales, where she - with her grand daughter. And the house was sold, some people bought 
it named Lovelace, but they wanted the whole house, because she'd - she'd - got girls who used to work for her - doing needlework, you know, she used to have a work room there. Oh and - oh yes, there was one barbers there. There was - another - lady - lad
y
 barber there, ladies hairdresser. I can't remember their name. There was no more shops along there until you got - about three doors from the top of Portobello Road was this old man, Mr Tanner, and he had birds - I - he had pigeons and - goldfish and - w
hite mice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So it was nearly all shops and tradesmen round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
There was only - only three shops on this side of the road. And then there was the - Guild - I've forgotten the man's name, he had a - a Sunday school and it still is a Sunday school
. It - it was a house, but - there was rooms upstairs and - they had - singing up there and - women's meeting and all that - they were - not Church of England - they - they were - Protestant but - minis - ministers you know what I mean, could - they could
 have been Congregational, I don't know, but they weren't Roman Catholics and they weren't Church of England. Because sometimes the Salvation Army used to stand outside there and play. And that's when I followed them to Shepherds Bush.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did Mr and Mrs Green live at the same house as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, they had the - they - use - you see there was four floors. There was under the grating, there - there was - two rooms - and a big coal cellar under the grating, there was gratings you could look down and s
ee into their kitchen, and then they had a bedroom and their parlour was on the next floor. Well then up - one flight of stairs was the - the - this little anteroom, that could have been a kitchen, but that's where we used to play and the toilet was there
. And then - there was our five rooms upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Which house is this now, 373, Portobello Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? I can't hear you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Is this the house at 373 Portobello?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, 373 Portobello Road's where I was born, that was over the shop. I'm talking about - I - I - 407 was that number.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Portobello?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get on with the Greens, were they all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And then - when - Mrs Green went away we moved up to the top - of Ladbroke Gore and Portobello Road you see, well then of
 course I was away - I was away from there then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever have any trouble with landlords?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Any what? Oh no, no, we never had any trouble. The only trouble we had was - Mrs Green if we made a noise in the passage and - he was on night work, y
ou know, sometimes kids go in and out and make a noise. But apart from that no, he was a dear old man, he used to - he used to buy us - he - every Thursday, he used to be paid on Thursday, and ev - every Thursday - he used to send up either a - a - bag of
 
apples that he bought of Amsted's, that was a shop next door but one, that was the only shop then until we got up to Mr - a barbers shop and then a few doors away was only three shops on this side of the road - from the continuation where the Eagle is I'm
 
talking about, and - then we used to - he used to either bring us up a - a bag of biscuits, and - Christmas he gave us a shilling each. Always used to give us a - a shilling each at Christmas, us - us three girls. And of course my Sammy was grown up then.
 And that's when he first went in the Army I think he was about sixteen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember Mr Murphy the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. Do I remember him? He was huge and he used to walk about at night with this lantern alight - lantern alight on his - hanging i
n his belt, they were - policeman those days, not rashers of bacon like they are now. He was huge. And - they never had any children. And at the top of the road there, that's all parted off, there used to be a police box. And - there was always a policema
n
 on duty there. And when old Murphy was on - night duty - I don't know if they used to make tea there or something, I couldn't tell you, but - we always knew when he was on night duty because he used to stand out - used to stand with his hands like this, 
watching us. He said, where do you think you're going this time of night? I'm just going to see my boyfriend. Get up those stairs before I call you father down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did people get on with him, did they like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh - he was a lovely man. Well - w
hen they used to lock old Long Neil up, Long Neil his name was, we used to call him Long Nell - about every other week he used to be wheeled up to the police station on this trolly. He was - he was - a nice man if you know what I mean but when he'd had a 
c
ouple of drinks he'd - he'd start sparring about you know. And there used to be a woman go in there - always had a long - skirt on and a white apron, I think she used to work in a laundry, she used to have her hair scraped back, and - her name was Polly s
omething, well - she - when she got boozed she'd fight like a man. She was a terror. But - there was never any - never anything rough - that I can remember up here, no more than there is now. But - everybody knew Long Neil.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was there anybody in the area that people didn't like, and wanted to get rid of out of the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Only - only those Italians. But - in the mews - there was Tubbs the sweep, Hayes, Mr Hayes worked on the railway, then there was a shoeing forge there, we used to love to go in ther
e, Buns and they belonged to the - sins of - Sons of the Phoenix, and - we - we used to watch the band go out from there, carrying their banners. Next door to - next door to that was another sweep. Teddy Gray, and his son has only just retired carrying on
 
the business. He came to us the last time we had a - our fires here. Old Teddy Gray, he was a sweep. Next door to that was - Mr and Mrs Jewel, and - they had a - pony and a two wheeled trap. I don't know what they used to do for a living but they were ver
y posh. And underneath you see the horses were kept. We used to love to go in there and give them a carrot or a crust of bread. Because that was only - that backed onto our house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You were saying about the Italians.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, the Italians you see - th
ey had a - they used to make the ice cream, in - in the mews there, and fill the - fill their barrows up - fill their barrows up with the ice cream, but - Charlie Rear was the - name of the man, and - Rosie was his wife and then he had four or five childr
en, and - they were nice little kids, but - these Italian - men, well we used to think they were dreadful. My mother used to say don't - don't you let me know that you've been round that stable again. We only used to watch 'em - make the ice}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 cream and keep 
turning it round like this, no machine. They used to make it and then they used to sell a - Hokey-Pokey, a ha'penny a lump. Used to - it was like a slice of margarine. But - I don't think they ever did anybody any harm, it was just that my mother knew tha
t they were foreigners and you know what it was those days, if you saw a foreigner. If you saw a foreigner or a black man or a sailor walking along and you didn't touch them, you wouldn't have any luck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were there never any sort of trave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 ling people in this area of London? Gipsies or people like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
The gipsies used to go by here sometimes with their caravans down to the Scrubs. But - no people came to the door not for anything only - the insurance man or - that's all I can remember coming to th
e door. The insurance man we - we bought all our stuff out - mum used to buy all the dry stuff, the tea and sugar - and coffee and - and - everything on a Friday or Saturday, and then - the butchers - and vegetables and that we used to get in the week. Th
at's all it was. We never had any callers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember feeling in these times that your parents had a struggle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do I remember what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well, yes, when my father was in hospit
al yes. I do remember. Only too much. But - we never went hungry, I know - I know one day - I can remember we had a boiled egg for our dinner, and some rice with treacle on it. And my little sister came - in the other room to us - to my May and me, and sh
e
 said, do you know what? We said, no. She said, we had our breakfast for our dinner didn't we? Because of it - because it was a boiled egg, I can always remember. But we were never hungry and we never wanted, and - what we had was good plain wholesome foo
d. You had suet puddings, dumplings, and if - mum'd make a - a - great - big dumpling and tie it up in a cloth and you had slices of it with treacle on or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 marmalade}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  or jam, but it was good wholesome food, different to the stuff we get now. And when she used
 to roast a - roast a bit of beef or lamb - or mutton or whatever it was we had, you got basins of dripping out of it, and that's what we used to have in the winter, when we came home from school, a big dish in the fender - dripping toast. Oh we used to l
ove it. But we never - we never wanted for anything. We had clean clothes, they weren't - always elaborate but they were clean and we were kept clean. And we never owed anybody anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember there being a distinction between people who were craftsmen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? What, people who lived around, any distinction? No, the - either the men worked on the railway or they were dustmen or they served in shops. And there was a sweep - a greengrocers - and the butchers. Some lived over the shops and
 some didn't. Some had stalls and kept their barrows in the - in the mews, if they didn't have horses they kept all their stuff in the mews. And - no, there was nothing - nobody was any better than anybody else, that's that - that's why made us grow up as
 
we are. I mean I - I could - even as a - even as a child I could never understand - why - anybody was any better than anybody else. I mean right from a child I've been like that. I don't know what that was stuck into me but - as it's always said there are
 
always people - who - because of their position in life you're supposed to look up to. But there's nobody better than you, you are the child of the universe. And you have a perfect right to live like that, you're all God's children, and that was stuck int
o me and it is still now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you think your parents put that into you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
My parents were like that. There was never - my mother worked for some very very rich people, but there was never anything that they were any better. They were never snobs. Th
ere was the rich and the poor, those days. And most of the kids around - when we were children, as they left school, they were packed into good service - as kitchen maids and - and - and - the boys they - perhaps have a paper round or a milk round, then t
h
ey went to work in shops or - or - dustmen or - or - taking coal round or something, there was - that - that - that was this vicinity anyway. But there was never any - rows or quarrels, only what there is now, only at the pubs and we used to enjoy that. I
t's the frustration of this deafness that upsets me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Do you remember whether it was possible for somebody who was a poor family to get up to be part of the rich, could you move from poor into being rich? Were there people who did that do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, I - I don't remember - I - I don't remember - any - anybody being any - any different from - anybody else, the - the - only man that - we can remember, and I still talk to his daughter because I went to school with then they live in Chesterton Ro
ad, was - when - their name was Butt - Butt, and there were - Mr Butt and his two sons - and - one boy went out into the Army and he lost his arm, he's only got one arm, that boy's still alive, they call him Sparrow, and he lives with his sister, round in
 
- in - Chesterton Road. And - I know my dad came in one day and he said I've just seen Mr Butt and he's been made overseer - in the - in the - Post Office, he's served so many years and he wears a peaked cap, otherwise postmen used to wear funny little sq
u
are hats you know, like a - this - this shape hat it used to be, like that - that - that shape hat you see, just like that. And with a - a peak at both ends, and then - after that of course they had the real peaked cap, but - they used to wear funny littl
e
 hats then. Like the policemen wear today, I think they're ugly with those capes, they used to look lovely in their uniform with all their buttons - still everything changes. Yes, and I - I know my dad came in this night and he said - so mum - my mum said
,
 oh I am glad, Mrs Butt's such a lovely person. She had a crowd of kids, about twelve I think, and - he said, I - I saw Mr Butt, he said, and I shook hands with him and he asked me if I would go in the Eagle and have a drink, but my dad didn't go. I can r
emember that too. As I look back on things those little incidents come up but you can't think of them all at once.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You've told me all about the different jobs you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh yes, I couldn't go all over that again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you did the first job for the post office and the munitions job and the factory you worked at, I forget the name of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Clement Talbot's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have holidays with pay with those jobs do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I didn't work at - I - I didn't work there - holidays
 with pay from Clement Talbot's? No, all they paid us for was the - was the - a Bank Holiday, we were paid for Bank Holiday and we got - if we went in stock taking - you got - extra five shillings and - and - a lovely dinner. Those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
That's what I'm talking about on a Sunday when we used to go in there, that's when I was shut in. That was a - that was a - what - what we call now overtime, but - it was a motor works then. I can't rem - I can't remember the name o
f it now, you must know it, down in Barbary Road, great big place there. Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Warwick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, that's not the name, it's - oh - it's absolutely gone from me, in fact my husband's cousin is - is - is one of the - directors down there, I've never s
een him. My son's seen him. Whatever is the name of it. It - Clement Talbot's, they - were - they had a place at Hammersmith, that was the last job my husband had. Ten years after that he did nothing. Nothing at all. And he lost his pension.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What were you paid for the post office job when you first left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Was it very much? Did you give any of the money that you earnt in these jobs before you got married, did you give any of the money that you earned to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I gave it all to her, she gave us back what we should have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get on with the people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh, fine, this - this - blind person - is my daughter's - godmother, she - and - she's - nearly ninety, and she comes - they 
bring her to see me, 'cos she can't see and she's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 paralysed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
, she did all this knitting. Last time I saw her - about - three weeks ago, in fact I had a letter from her - yesterday, and this is a letter from her son who's just joined the boats. He's in the m
erchant navy. He's just - off - I didn't know the name of that boat and - until I looked at it this morning. That's the - years - well over sixty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you worked for Madam Collier, Mrs Collier, did she pay you or did you just live with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I used to get ten shillings and all me food, that was a lot. Those days. I can always remember - it was my birthday while I was there and she said - she went out for the day somewhere, and Mary, that was the - her - head cook and bottle washer etc etc -
 we turned all the room out and cleaned all the pictures, she had - oh dozens of pictures, and when she came back everywhere was shining beautifully, and she bought us each a pair of shoes. Gave us the money to buy a pair of shoes, she was so pleased, we 
t
ook the cushion covers off and washed them, and - we washed and - ironed the table - little table cloth she had, and - oh she had dozens of pictures all hanging on the wall, and - I can remember - I had an old wash leather glove, chamois glove and we clea
n
ed all the pictures, and when she came in she was thrilled to bits, she'd been out for the day. I think that's when she met these Heimphel's, these people who - who - who I - I went away - to - see that - they moved right near to my aunt that they bought 
this beautiful house, Covelly on the Lees, it had three }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 verandas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
 round it. Beautiful house. And of course I - I - went there and I got money and - and - well I lived with them. And of course I got married from there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did they give you money while you were working there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you get paid while you were there or just living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, I got pocket money while I was there, all I - all I wanted - I mean Christmas time - they bought - a - Christmas time they bought me a coat and - 
and - underclothes - I was like one of their own children. 'Course I had been very ill just before I went down there, then of course - my hus - husband came down, and - he stayed at - he stayed with my aunt and uncle, and he took a job as a milk roundsman
,
 to Suitors, and then we were married and we moved into Seaview Road, Southend. We lived there and - two years then my daughter was born, then the war broke out and of course we came back up here to - to - to my mum's, and - our furniture was bought up, w
hat there was left of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your husband stay on as a milkman when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Was your husband still a milkman when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh - he was - he - he was working for Suitors, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever do any evening classes or anything like that for any of these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Did I - do any - no - the only evening classes that I - I ever went to - was - from - from the church - to - two nights a week, to - Tuesdays and Thursdays and sometimes on a Friday we used to go to
 the mission, and - Tuesdays and - was - needlework, knitting - and - Thur - Thursdays was games. And Fridays was - like a Band of Hope. And then sometimes on Wednesday about once a month we used to have missionaries come over there and we used to go ther
e for the evening, and my dad used to come and meet us. That's you - I never went to any evening classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You never did any sort of apprenticeship or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No. No, I - I got in - on me own initiative in the - in the - with t
he marks from school, with - it wasn't O levels or A levels and all that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
You know when you went to Southend Technical School just for the last few months, did you take any exams there or were all the exams done over here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh - that - that's wh
ere I - that was where I went when I left that school because there was no - places you could go if - if you won a scholarship, you had to go to these technical - places, well - I was only there a little while. And - I can't remember how long, funnily eno
ugh my daughter - grand daughter's living nearly opposite, in Saltram Crescent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What kind of things did you do at Southend Technical, the same as here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I - I - I - arithmetic and - general knowledge and - I think only three months I was there because - I - I - you - you had to be fo}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
rteen before you left, you see, and I - and - I was only about thirteen and a half when I went down there. No, I didn't do - I didn't do anything there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you ever a member of any trade union or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Never belonged to anything of that - nor did my father. My father was just a Liberal, we never belonged to anything. Nothing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your never father actually took part in any political organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. No, he was just a Liberal, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever feel there were any division of interests amongst -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 As what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever feel there were any division of interests amongst workers in those day, in the places where you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No - what - what do you mean, they - they had a - tennis and that sort of thing, I never went in for anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you think there was any difference between those who were skilled and those who were not skilled?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. I went there as a sorter - and I went - everywhere
 I went I went as a clerk, a cost - costing clerk - at the ABC and - when I did - soldiers and sailors deceased - belongings, across the road, it was - it had been a - Embassy of some sort because it was a beautiful house, but all the - mantel - pieces an
d all the doors were covered with match}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 boarding, beautiful. And the staircase was all covered.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When did you do that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 After I left Clement Talbot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s and I was there 'til I - my husband come home from the war. Unfortunately I - had to leave to
 go down and manage that blooming shop. And that was the final until - I had my son. Then eighteen months when he - he was eighteen months old I went to work at the hospital, my husband - had had this operation, had a piece of his rib taken out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you think that your full time work when you left school and started work changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No, I haven't, because I believe in - living today. And hoping for tomorrow. You see, there's no yesterdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You don't think there was any change when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No. Not - not - not in my way of living. I - I - I've got - I - I've got a - I'm not religious - I don't believe in going to church, I would go if I were well enough, but - I believe in prayer and I believe
 - in - reading Psalms - and - I love - watching the - religious programmes on here. But - I hate any - I hate - blasphemy and drink, the results thereof I - I - I hate that. And - I always have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did everybody go to church in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We
ll most - most people did round here, there used to be the mothers meeting. But my mum never - never had time to go. Used to be the mothers meeting over the church, all the old people used to go. The mothers outing and all that. Only once - only once were
 
we allowed to go to a Sunday school outing and we went - in the brakes to Kew Garden, I think it was Kew Garden so I know the river was running by there somewhere. And - that's the only time that we were allowed to go. But of course as regards school jour
n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 ey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 s or anything of that then - the only thing that - we went to was two years in succession we went to children}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
s country holiday fund. That was the only holidays that we ever had. But - we were taken out, we - we weren't kept - we never run the streets, w
e were taken up to Kensington Gardens, in fact we knew all the - all the path there I think, and only - on one occasion - we went up there, there was a regatta or something up there as far as I remember and my dad took - took us, and mum as well, we went 
u
p to the Serpentine, and watched them - swimming and what have you, standing on the bridge, and - and - and we had - we - we had tea there, they - they made tea and - and - I can remember now - my - my mum was saying about how much it cost, only - in a wa
y she was saying - we couldn't always afford to do this or something of that. But we never wanted, we never had drink in our home. My dad used to smoke a pipe.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you still go to church after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Do - did I still go to chur
ch? Yes, I tell you on one occasion I went to church. While I was living - with my aunt - we had a - friend come down and she stayed with the people next door, my auntie couldn't put her up. Because she had regular - people living with her, and - a family
 
- and we - there was a missionary that came over from Japan. And he - was at a church in Southend. Well - Gladys - came in on the Sunday morning and she said - will you come to church - with me tonight to see - I've forgotten the man's name now. I think i
t
 was Tomlinson. His - he's come - he - he's been to - Africa and Japan and Holland and - I don't know where he hadn't been, in a whole year, and he was coming back here to see - the Reverend somebody who was his brother or cousin, so she said, I heard tha
t
 we'll go and see him, we'll go to the church and talk, to him afterwards. Well - we're going along, it was beautiful sunshine. I've got a - lovely white frock and all done up to there. We're walking along, and suddenly there was a terrible storm. We were
 
- it was pelting with rain and fortunately - we were pass - just passing the church - on the way to Southend - between Westcliffe and Southend, so we hopped inside the church and the vicar was up in the pulpit - and he looked straight at us and he said, s
o
me people used the church as an umbrella, so we put a penny each in the box and ran out. But he didn't mean it for us. Some people use the church as an umbrella, well - we stood outside there in fits. When we got to the church of course the service was ov
e
r and we went - we went and - in the vestry and we were talking to this Reverend or whatever he was, so - missionary - preacher, so - we told him what had happened. So he said, did you know the meaning of that? So I said, yes. People - go to church - in m
y
 estimation I said to learn something - or to hear something - that - if something bad has happened that - you can protect yourself from it or - or get the help through - through faith. I said, I don't - that's - that's my philosophy, I said, that's all I
 know. Well, he said, it's a very good philosophy in any way. But we never forgot that, the fun we had, when we got back and told my aunt and uncle they were in fits. I was drowned, absolutely. But wasn't it a funny thing, to pop in like that? We -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Whereabouts did your auntie live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
3 Finchley Road, Westcliffe, turning out of Valcarn Road, two minutes from West - from Westcliffe Station. Westcliffe Station - is here. Down there leads to the front and Colvelly, a house there, coming up here - there'
s Finchley Road - the top of Valcarny Road is London Road. That leads to Southend and that leads to Leigh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you living at home still while you were doing this post office job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh yes. Yes, that's where I had me first bike and nearly broke me neck.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you came back with your husband from Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, we lived down - down there for some time, I - I never saw my mother or father - oh - they were - they were - honest to say they were disgusted because - I got married,
 my father wasn't so bad but my mother was very very very upset. Of course I can realize it now but I didn't think I'd done any harm. I wanted him, I loved him and I married him. And I loved him more than - any - any other man. My - they always hoped that
 
I'd marry this Ernie, because his - his - his mother died - she was a widow and she used to go out to laundry work, and he was always in and out of our place, our home, and - he went to live at Bognor, and his uncle died and left him a coal - merchant bus
i
ness, and the next time I saw him I was married - living here - and - he came up to see my mum and he went up to the old house and they told him where I live - we lived, and of course mum had died. And dad. I never saw him any more. He spoke to my husband
 and - 'course they remembered each other from boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you'd known your husband since you were five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Five years old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He just came from up the road,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we used to sit - they used to live 333 Ladbroke Grove. He'd got a - one siste
r Annie, a brother Henry older than him, then there was my husband, Joseph - with his coat of many colours - he was the biggest devil out, and - that's why I liked him, and - Albert, that's the boy that was drowned, and Will was the youngest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he go to the same school as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, they went to the Catholic school. That was the trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you save up money before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we didn't save much money, we had a few pounds that's all. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Were you engaged before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Yes, I - I - I had a - I had a big - gold keeper - ring, plain gold ring. 'Cos this ring was my mother's, that's over a hundred years old. And that was my silver wedding ring, that platinum. All the rest of the stuff I had that was my moth
er's I've given away except that ring, and this brooch - was presented to my husband when he was out in France, with my birthstone in, that's a real topaz, that's all I've got, all the other stuff was stolen what I didn't give to my nieces and nephews.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you have things like eternity rings at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Did I ever have what? I can't - an eternity, ring, no, I had this keeper, and - oh I had a little - gold - I had a little gold - oh I had a signet ring with my initials in, but I bought - my husband 
bought for us both, and it had - his initials, J, on mine and on his - he had S, and inside was the inscription, during the war, 1914, and - while I was working he lost his, and while I was working up at the office I caught it in the - in the - they had -
 
a - to open the drawers - all the tables were green iron and very long and as I went to open this drawer I caught the - caught this ring, and it broke. Well I - I took it off, I left it off and I put it in the box. And - just before - my daughter died - n
o, since my daughter died, I had it mended, because my - Janette, this J - and it's still got the - the - the whole}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
ring itself but they put a new shank on it, a man round the corner, and I've given it to Janette. Now she's going to save it, but her little 
girl is Joanne so she said, I don't know whether to save it for Joanne or to give it to John. You see? So I said, well if you give it to John - I said - possibly - I said, you've got two nice rings I said, you can save that for Janette. But the signet rin
g, I said, I would like you to give to John. I said when he's fourteen, but I said you please yourself what you do. Well then the last time my brother came up here, my John - I went out - we went out with him and he brought me a beautiful row of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 Ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 iro pearl
s in Reget Street. Well I wore them for a long time. And - while I was working up there - I had them restrung and they charged me three pound to restring them and put another gold catch on them. Well I gave those to Janette. In a - they were in a little y
ellow case, I gave them to here, after my daughter died. And - several different - things that I had, but that picture of me where I'd got that - that lovely - brooch on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How long were you engaged for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I - I don't know, he - he bought me this ring I suppose - when he came - down to my aunt's and - about a couple of years I suppose.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Do you remember if your parents helped you in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? No, they didn't. No. No, they did not. My mother and - only - only - only - only
 my John, my eldest brother, he - he came up to see us once and it was on my birthday and he gave me a pound note, or gave me - yes, a pound note, that's all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did your parents come to your wedding? Who was at the wedding then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Two people came a
 Mr and Mrs Finnimore. Two - the girl - was a - cook, and her husband - was a milkman. They came. I was married in a registry office because my husband was a Catholic and then when we - we were received in the church. And I never saw - I never saw my moth
e
r or anybody belonging to me, only my sister May came down to see us when we lived there. I never saw my mother until - 'til the - my Phyllis was born - in the September, the eleventh of September, and - I never got over that - properly over that confinem
ent, and - in the November - my father came down. And he bought me back to London. My mother-in-law had my baby, and I was three months and a fortnight in St Mary's hospital, was followed by a pupil }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 septicaemia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 , and I was three months and a fortnight in Vic
toria Ward, and they were so ill they baptized my baby in there. And my mother came to see me while I was in there. And she was working then, she was a cook - then for Mr and Mrs Macata who afterwards are - relation to the Franklins - Montefouries, and I 
w
as in their bed, over my bed was the inscription - Lord and Lady Montefouries that was the bed that I happened to be in, because when they knew that I was in the hospital they came in to see me, and my baby was - was baptized in there because they thought
 
I was going to die. And she was three months old then. That was in November. And I was in there - three months and - three months and three weeks. And when I had my son, he was born in St Mary's hospital, I was in St Mary's hospital, and it was during the
 
time that I was in St Mary's hospital - when my - daughter was a baby that my husband moved the furniture up here. Of course then we were all friends naturally. And - and after that - I came out - I - came out from the - I came out from the hospital - and
 - my husband went to work - when I was able to - carry - carry - carry on you see the - the - the war broke out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When the war broke out did you go and live with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we moved - we moved up here to Chesterton Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Wasn't there a time when you lived with your parents again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I never lived with my parents after I was married. No, there was none of that. You were out and you were out, if you wanted any help or - if you if any - they could do anything, well then - my son was born when my daughter }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 was ten, and I was in that press}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
ing shop at that time. I came out of the house one morning to go shopping. And I was knocked down by a bicycle. I was hit full pelt in the stomach as I' - went across the road. Well I had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid281643\charrsid5646288 
haemorrhage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288  an
d I went to the hospital. They examined me, Doctor Wilfred Harris was the man, a big - professional - man he was, and he said, would - he asked my mother's advice, if they should take the baby. So - my mother said, no, because the baby was alive. Well - I
 
had to - I had to go backwards and forwards to that hospital every other day - for treatment. With injections and I don't know what else. Well - on the eleventh of August - twenty-fifth of August - my other granddaughter's the eleventh of August, on the t
w
enty-fifth of August, my - son was born. Well - he was born with a broken arm, that was done - he - his arm was - was like that, and I had a terrible confinement. I was put up in the top ward - and - I was in there three weeks - before they left me come o
u
t. Another person who lived in Wharf Road - the back of Paddington Station, her husband was a dustman, and she - was having her second child. She was coming in the hospital to have this baby, and her - other child had whooping cough, so - she sent round w
h
en she was in labour, she sent round to the hospital for the doctors to come out to her. You see? She had her mother to look after. During the time that she was in labour, I mean - I mean this is natural if - you can listen if you like, she was in labour,
 
her husband was at work and her mother was pottering about the place, waiting for the doctor to come. And she penetrated the babies head with a glove stretcher. Well - I'm in the hospital then, I didn't know the woman - well they - bought the woman in and
 
the baby. And I was going out on the following Wednesday. I was - sitting up on the Sunday evening, my husband came in, and - he bought me a big - bunch of grapes, and some sweets, and I said - oh I'll share them round I said, and - there was only four of
 
us in the ward, and - this person that was bought in, she was put in a side ward with her baby, you see, because of the infection, the - her child had had whooping cough, so she was in there, there was a - white sheet over the door, and before the doctors
 
went in and out there, being as it was a maternity ward, Zoonz - Zoons ward it was the name of the ward, in St Mary's hospital, Paddington, look out right onto Prade Street, the balcony did, and - you got - anyway, I - was so excited that I was going home
 
on the Wed - on the Wednesday, my husband bought my clothes and the baby clothes, he went home on the Sunday - evening, and - we were allowed Sunday evening visiting then, and - the - a little nurse that was on, sister was off duty, and we'd all fed our b
a
bies, I breast fed my babies, both of them, and - the - there was a little charge - a little staff charge nurse on there, so she came round to me, and she said, oh Mrs Freeman, she said, will you give - Sandy's mother - has been taken down for a X-ray, so
 
she said, will you give him his bottle? So she put the baby into my arms, and I gave the baby his bottle. She came and took him away - and - I - they bought the supper round, and - she - or the milk rather, and - she - she - took him away and put him back
 
in his cot. In the night I was terribly sick, they called the specialist in. Called the doctor in, they sent for the specialist, I'd got pubertal septicaemia, that I'd caught from that child. I was in there four months - four months and a half then. And -
 
I was - I - I was unconscious for ten days. I don't remember being taken out of that ward, my husband nearly went mad. Well I was taken into the isolation block that looked right out onto the Paddington station, right the other side of the hospital, and i
t
 was all isolation, I was in a little private ward and next door was a doctor that was awarded, he'd had the measles. He used to run up and down the corridor with a - a ty train you know, and - oh we were really isolated there. Well we had the time of our
 
lives when I did become conscious because I had champagne and - the middle of the night when after - night sister had been round, we used to have - sandwiches and what have you and - what haven't you, but they kept my son in there all that time - so I sai
d
 to this doctor one days I said, do you think my baby - I can be taken down to see my baby? So he said, no. So I said, well can you bring my baby up here? No, certainly not. So he said, I will go down and see your son. He said - he wasn't baptized here, h
e
 was baptized over the road, he said, I will go down and see your son, and - I will bring a message back from him. Next morning he came up and he asked me how I was and I said I was very much better. When I became conscious my sister was sitting the side 
o
f me and I thought it was the devil, and I said oh don't - don't sit there looking at me. So - my sister went and this doctor came up to me, no, he said, I want you to sit quiet - quietly, he said and I want you to talk to me, he said, and I want you to a
n
swer my questions, but he said, I want you to think. So - he said I've brought a message from your baby, he is the only boy baby with twelve ladies and he won't have anything to do with them whatsoever. So we had a laugh about that. So he said, now, I wan
t
 you to tell me exactly how you felt, he said - after you'd vomited. Well I said, I just felt - that I'd fallen in the water. But I said, I - I tried to get out and I couldn't because my arms wouldn't move. I said, and - and I said, I could feel myself si
n
king, but I said, the water only come up to here. He wrote it all down. And - I said I could hear the roaring of water but - it never came near me. It was in the distance. - He wrote that all down. And he said - did you have - did you see any vision, any 
f
ace? So I said, no, I said, I looked up, I said, and I thought it was the moon but it was an electric light. And then I said I saw my sister sitting by the side of me. He said, that's when you became conscious. He said, I'll tell you something now, if tha
t
 water - in - your unconsciousness had come up over your mouth you would have died. So he said I've written this all down and it was all printed in the Lancet. So - of course when I came out of the hospital there's me baby all dressed beautifully, and - s
i
ster from the - isolation came down to the cab. And - they all came and saw me off, so - the next day - they said - would you - if you feel well enough, of course I was well because I hadn't been able to get up after that for about another three weeks, so
 
- but they kept me still upstairs, they said, will you - can you come back tomorrow or the next day? So I said, well I must have a day at home, I said, to get - settled. He said, well - can I make an appointment for you to see me on Thursday. And that was
 
his day at the hospital. Doctor Wilfred Harris, a lovely man he was. Jewish but a fine man. So he said, I want to see you, he said, before the hospital committee. When I went in the room they asked me and my husband if I wanted to make any claim because -
 I caught that infection in there. So I said, no, nothing at all, I said, I am only too grateful that I'm able to go home with my son is perfect, I'm feeling well, I said, and my husband had got a job and - I said, I don't want to hear any more about it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did your husband manage while you were in hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh he was round at his mother's in Action Road, that's where she lived. He was round there, backwards and forwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about the time you were in hospital with Phyllis for three and a half months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I wasn't in hospital with Phyllis, I - that's what I say, I had her at home that's how I got this blood poisoning, from this dirty old woman. She - I wasn't washed clean and I didn't know anything about it. What could - that's when Phyl
lis was born. And that's ten years after I had Bernard. But - Bernard was born in the hospital. But it was nothing to do with the accident, that was - I mean he was born perfectly - in - in - sight and hearing and everything, only that he'd got this twist
e
d arm. 'Cos that was done through the accident you see. But if my mother and father had consented - they would have take - taken him at the seven months, because they - they didn't know whether he - he'd be born paralyzed or anything, but I knew he was al
ive. So - that's how - how he was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you breast fed both the babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 So - I never wanted any more babies after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you breast fed both Phyllis and Bernard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I started to breast feed Bernard but of course when - when - I came out of the hospital - he was put on Glaxo.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about Phyllis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Oh yes, I - I - well Phyllis was ten years old. No, I fed her - and I had a - a Jewish doctor, Doctor Midgeley Reeves he was, and - he - he came in and - at the confinement
 and Mrs Glews, that was the landlady of the house, and it was her mother or mother-in-law, she used to go round look - looking after people who had babies. But - she was - oh she was a horrible dirty old woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you enjoy feeding Phyllis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well - it was natural, I mean there wasn't anything - to - to go against it, it came to me as a natural thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 But apparently quite a lot of people used a bottle even in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh no, I never - my Phyllis never - never had a bottle, I - I fe
d her until she was nearly nine months old. And my boy walked at nine months, my husband had had this operation, they'd taken a piece of his - piece of the rib out, he had it in a matchbox for ages, and - that's where they found the cancer when he died ye
ars after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever have any difficulties in breast feeding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Diffi - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You didn't get advice off anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Never had - any trouble at all, and - of course this poor little nurse, she was reprimanded but it wasn't her fault
. I mean she was only sent up there to help with the suppers. But - of course we could have made a lot of fuss but I was only too thankful to - to be there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 If Phyllis was asleep would you wake her for a feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What when she - when she was a baby? I - I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 If she cried before the normal time would you feed her then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
I - she - was a baby - that was born - I fed her - at certain times, she was a baby that hardly ever cried, and she was a lovely person until she died, she neve
r caused me a moment's anxiety, only when she was ill. I never had any worry at all with her. And a person who came in here yesterday morning was talking about her. She said, I'll never forget the day of her funeral. They all used to joke together, Mary P
e
arce and this Gill - they're married women, live along here, they always used to joke together, and - she said, it was the greatest surprise in my life, she said, when Phyll died. I said, it was to a good many people. I never had any trouble with her and 
I
 don't think in all the years - I had her she ever answered me back. If I told her to do a thing, she would use her own discretion, she - if she asked me anything I would tell her, to the best of my ability, and apart from that - she used her own discreti
on and she - as she did with her own children. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When you had Phyllis, you had her at home, that was in Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And you had a nurse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Yes. And the doctor. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 And this old woman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Well, this was - it was this woman
 who came - came in and her daughter, Mrs Glews used to come up and - and cook the food although my husband used to - do that, he - and - the old girl used to do the washing. And - the baby's nappies and that, but - of course I only had the doctor to the 
confinement. I - didn't - didn't go in hospital those days. 'Cos they had the nurses all round here, the same as they did, but I had my boy in St Mary's hospital, because of the accident.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You got this disease and you had to go into St Mary's hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? When I went up to - after - for three months I was ill down at - down at Westcliffe, and - and I saw the doctor down there, and he just gave me tablets and that, but - and - medicine because I was sick, I've forgotten his name now, Doctor Reg
 or somebody, and - my father came down and my father bought me back - home, and the next day I went to - St Mary's hospital, and they kept me in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Where did Phyllis go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 My other-in-law had her, I told you, she had her all the time. She had all t
he time that I was in there, when - when I went in there she was four months old. September, October, November - no, November I went in, August, September, October, November, three months old she was and my mother-in-law had her all the time, and my husba
nd used to go there for all his food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Wouldn't it be dangerous to breast feed the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
Pardon? I didn't - I didn't feed her after that, I only - only fed her for the first three months. But - it didn't affect her in - in - any way. Because my mo
ther in law put her on cows milk and barley water, that's what she was brought up on. But my son had Glaxo. Milk and - and - and - cows milk - milk and barley water and - groats and - that sort of thing she was fed on. She wasn't fed on the stuff they giv
e kids now, cheese and all that stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 When did you wean her, how old would she be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Four month.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 To go right back to the wedding when you first got married, you say that your parents didn't go to the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, we went - we - we
 - we bought the - we bought this - this - furniture that we wanted, it wasn't much, it was - we had two rooms, one was a - we had a kitchen table and some chairs and - in the front room we had two armchairs and - and a bed and wardrobe and a chest of dra
wers and - that's all we started with, but we done - we didn't owe anybody anything, we bought those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 What about his parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, they never came near, never saw him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you get on with his parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh I got on very well with them because I'd spent so much time with them when I was a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You'd been going round there since you were about five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Oh yes, right - we - I was always in their place, he never - he never came in our house, not for - not until - oh, we was grown
 up. My father liked him and - my mother didn't dislike him but - it was - it was the difference in the religion. And his people used to drink and - and - that was the only difference between us, we - we didn't - the parents didn't agree. But it was a -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Who were the Finnimores?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Finnimores were the two people at our wedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How did you meet them, were they people in Westcliffe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No, they lived in Southend, she was a cook and he was a milkman. That's how we met them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How old was your husband when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 We were both twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Your husband's job was a milkman when you got married? What did he do before he became a milkman, what did he start off as?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Before he got married, he was a painter and decorator, and - m
aking loose curtains and covers, upholstery and - he was an art decorator entirely. He made loose covers and curtains and - and - moulding of - that lovely over - mantel I've got in the other room he made. Like - what I want - my grand daughter to have wh
e
n I can get it over there. But with my - grandson with - with my daughter's husband - granddaughter's husband my dear - God help her. I wouldn't - I've asked him to come over and get it, no, I'll have to pay for it to go over there, they won't - come and 
fetch it. Still I'm not worried about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He carried on this art decorator work all his life really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He loved that work did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 He didn't - he - he didn't start work for - for Sir Edwin Lutchensuntil - we came
 back here - and lived in Chesterton Road, before we went down to the shop. Before that he worked for - different big firms in London. For - I can't remember who he worked for now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did you ever punish Phyllis when she was naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did I ever what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 You say you never had any trouble with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 No. I can't remember ever slapping her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 How much did your husband have to do with the children when they were very little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon? Oh don't talk about it, God Almighty, the grandchildren 
and all. We never got a look in. With - my two grandchildren, especially that - eldest one. He - he made a god almighty of her, he used to take her to school and bring her home and - while the war was on. And - we left her down at Cambridge, with my - son
-
in-law's - cousins, and - he was missing all one day, and he - went down and brought her back, she went to school down there and he went and brought her back. He said, your father - your father's in France he said, and - you should be here with your mothe
r and your grandmother so that what - that's what happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever help feed or bath Phyllis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Only the boy. My son, not the girls naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever help get them to sleep or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Did he ever to help to get them to go to sleep or sort of lullabies and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, I mean they - they lived in their upstairs - they had the flat upstairs and we had a - the flat - below, he - he - didn't have anything to do with them only to meet them fro
m school. And all the time they lived here, when my son-in-law come home from the war, I never went up in their flat, only when I was invited.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I'm thinking more of your actual children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16392069 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 I'm thinking of your children before they grew
 up, Bernard and Phyllis as children, did your husband have much to do with them in the way of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11557774 SF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15806095\charrsid5646288 
No, he - no, I - I don't know quite what you mean, I - I mean - I always - I always bathed them and fed them, he used to bath the boy and - cut his hair and all that, but - apart from that I always looked after them.
\par }}